{"title_page": "Memory improvement", "text_new": "{{more medical citations needed|date=August 2015}}\n[[File:Hippocampus small.gif|thumb|The hippocampus regulates memory function.]]\n'''Memory improvement''' is the act of improving one's memory. Memory deficits, age-related memory loss, and people's want to improve their own memory has lead to research on how to best help people to improve their memory. Research has also worked to determine what factors influence memory and cognition. Many different techniques to improve memory have been found, including [[cognitive training]], [[Psychopharmacology|psychopharmacology,]] [[Diet (nutrition)|diet]], [[stress management]], and [[exercise]]. Each technique has the ability to influence memory in a different ways. [[Neuroimaging]] has also provided [[Neuroscience|neurobiological]] evidence supporting [[Holism|holistic]] ways in which one can improve memory.\n\n==Memory function factors==\n\n=== Neuroplasticity===\n[[Neuroplasticity]] is the mechanism by which the brain encodes experience, learns new behaviours and relearns lost behaviour if the brain has been damaged.<ref name=\"Kleim\">Kleim, JA., & Jones, TA. (2008). [http://www.bridgesnky.org/uploads/2016_Experience-Dependent_Neuroplasticity.pdf Principles of experience-dependent neural plasticity: implications for rehabilitation after brain damage]. Journal of Speech, Language, and Hearing Research, 51, S225-S239.</ref>\n\n[[File:Hackney carriage.jpg|thumb|London Taxicab]]Experience-dependent neuroplasticity suggests that the brain changes in response to what it experiences. [[London]] [[taxicab]] drivers provide a great example of this dynamic. They undergo extensive training for 2\u20134 years, learning and memorizing street names, layout of streets within the city and the quickest cross-city routes.  After studying London taxicab drivers over a period of time, it was found that the [[grey matter]] volume increased over time in the posterior [[hippocampus]], an area in the brain involved heavily in memory. The longer taxi drivers navigated the streets of London, the greater the posterior hippocampal gray matter volume.  This suggests a correlation between a healthy person's mental training or exercise and their brains capacity to manage greater volume and more complex information. The increase in volume actually led to a decrease in the taxi drivers' ability to acquire new visuo-spatial information.<ref name=\"Maguire\">Maguire, EA., Woollett, K., & Spiers, HJ. (2006). [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Hugo_Spiers/publication/6769737_London_Taxi_Drivers_and_Bus_Drivers_A_Structural_MRI_and_Neuropsychological_Analysis/links/09e41508a947d83c7a000000.pdf London taxi drivers and bus drivers]: a structural MRI and neuropsychological analysis. ''Hippocampus'', 16, 1091-1101.</ref>\n\n===Stress===\nResearch has found that chronic and acute stress have adverse effects on memory processing systems. Therefore, it is important to find mechanisms in which one can reduce the amount of stress in their lives when seeking to improve memory.\n\n* '''[[Chronic stress]]''' has been shown to have negative impacts on the brain, especially in [[Memory#Processes|memory processing]] systems.<ref name=\"Mizoguchi\">Mizoguchi, K., Mitsutoshi, Y., Ishige, A., et al. (2000). [http://www.jneurosci.org/content/20/4/1568.long Chronic Stress Induces Impairment of Spatial Working Memory Because of Prefrontal Dopaminergic Dysfunction]. The Journal of Neuroscience Vol 20(4) 1568-1574.</ref> The hippocampus is vulnerable to repeated stress due to adrenal steroid stress hormones.<ref>Jacobson, L. & Sapolsky, R.M. [http://press.endocrine.org/doi/pdf/10.1210/edrv-12-2-118 The role of the hippocampus in feedback regulation of the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis]. Endo. Rev. 12, 118\u2212134 (1991).</ref>  Elevated [[glucocorticoids]], a class of [[Adrenal cortex|adrenal]] [[steroid hormone]]s, results in increased [[cortisol]], a well known stress response hormone in the brain,<ref>Starkman, M. N., Gebarski, S. S., Berent, S. & Schteingart, D. E. (1992). [https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/handle/2027.42/29769/0000107.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y Hippocampal formation volume, memory dysfunction, and cortisol levels in patients with Cushing's syndrome]. ''Biol. Psychiatry'' 32, 756\u2212765.</ref> and glucocorticoids are known to affect memory.<ref name=\"McEwen\">McEwen, B.S. (1999). [https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/ed19/1283e8be2c70a4f9aa0bc87eb6f51f33b99d.pdf Stress and Hippocampal Plasticity]. Annual Review of Neuroscience. Vol. 22: 105-122.</ref> Prolonged high cortisol levels, as seen in chronic stress, have been shown to result in reduced hippocampal volume as well as deficits in hippocampal-dependent memory, as seen in impaired [[Declarative memory|declarative]], [[Episodic memory|episodic]], [[Spatial memory|spatial]], and [[Context-dependent memory|contextual]] memory performance.<ref name=\"McEwen\"/>  Chronic, long-term high cortisol levels affect the degree of hippocampal atrophy, resulting in as much as a 14% hippocampal volume reduction and impaired hippocampus-dependent memory when compared to elderly subjects with decreased or moderate cortisol levels.<ref name=\"McEwen\"/><ref>Squire, L. R. (1992). [http://whoville.ucsd.edu/PDFs/188_Squire_PsychRev_1992.pdf Memory and the hippocampus : A synthesis from findings with rats, monkeys, and humans]. Psychol. Rev. 99, 195\u2212231.</ref><ref name=\"Sapolsky\">Sapolsky, R. M., Krey, L. C. & McEwen, B. S. (2002) The neuroendocrinology of stress and aging: The glucocorticoid cascade hypothesis. Endo. Rev. 7, 284\u2212301.</ref> An example ''may'' be found in the London taxi drivers, as the anterior hippocampus was hypothesized to decrease in volume as a result of elevated cortisol levels from stress.<ref name=\"Maguire\"/>{{#tag:ref|Quote from Maguire: \"Increases in plasma or salivary cortisol are often used as a biochemical marker of stress. Elevated cortisol levels have been associated with poor performance on memory tasks (Newcomer et al., 1999; Cho et al., 2000) and reduced hippocampal volume (Lupien et al., 1998). Thus, stress may have induced the anterior hippocampal volume reduction in the taxi drivers.\"<ref name=\"Maguire\"/>|group=\"nb\"}}\n* '''[[Fight-or-flight response|Acute stress]],''' a more common form of stress, results in the release of adrenal steroids resulting in impaired short-term and working memory processes such as [[selective attention]], [[memory consolidation]], as well as long-term potentiation.<ref>Lupien SJ, McEwen BS. 1997. The acute effects of corticosteroids on cognition: integration of animal and human model studies. Brain Res. Rev. 24:1\u201327.</ref><ref>McEwen, B.S. (1998). [https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/ee3c/1a87d21b1865abe72157226e38103b0d95cf.pdf Protective and damaging effects of stress mediators]. New Engl. J. Med. 238, 171\u2212179.</ref>  The human brain has a limited [[short-term memory]] capacity to process information, which results in constant competition between stimuli to become processed. [[Executive functions|Cognitive control]] processes such as selective attention reduce this competition by prioritizing where attentional resources are distributed.  Attention is crucial in memory processing and enhances encoding and strength of memory traces.<ref name=\"Shiffrin\">Shiffrin, R.M. (1976). Capacity limitations in information processing, attention, and memory. In W.K. Estes (Ed.), Handbook of learning and cognitive processes (Vol. 4). Hillsdale, NJ: Erlbaum.</ref> It is therefore important to selectively attend to relevant information and ignore irrelevant information in order to have the greatest success at remembering.<ref name=\"Slagter\">Slagter, H.A., Lutz, A., Greischar, L.L., Francis, A.D., Nieuwenhuis, S., Davis, J.M., Davidson, R.J. (2007). [http://journals.plos.org/plosbiology/article?id=10.1371/journal.pbio.0050138 Mental Training Affects Distribution of Limited Brain Resources].  PLoS Biol Vol 5(6).</ref>\n\n:Animal and human studies provide evidence as they report that acute stress impairs the maintenance of [[short-term memory]] and [[working memory]] and aggravates [[Neuropsychiatry|neuropsychiatric]] disorders involved in short-term and working memory such as [[Depression (mood)|depression]] and [[schizophrenia]].<ref name=\"Mizoguchi\"/> Animal studies with rats have also shown that exposure to acute stress reduces the survival of hippocampal neurons.<ref name=\"Tang\">Tang, Y.Y., Ma, Y. Wang, Y., Fan, Y. Et al. (2007). [http://www.pnas.org/content/104/43/17152.full Short-term meditation training improves attention and self-regulation]. PNAS. vol. 104 no. 43 17152-17156.</ref>\n\n:One of the roles of the [[central nervous system]] (CNS) is to help adapt to stressful environments.<ref name=\"Mizoguchi\"/> It has been suggested that acute stress may have a protective function for individuals more vulnerable to their own stress hormones. Some individuals, for example, are not able to decrease or habituate their cortisol elevation, which plays a major role in hippocampal atrophy.<ref>Kirschbaum C, Prussner JC, Stone AA, Federenko I, Gaab J. 1995. [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Clemens_Kirschbaum/publication/14647264_Kirschbaum_C_Prussner_JC_Stone_AA_Federenko_I_Gaab_J_Lintz_D_Schommer_N_Hellhammer_DH._Persistent_high_cortisol_responses_to_repeated_psychological_stress_in_a_subpopulation_of_healthy_men/links/0912f50f7b25435a39000000.pdf Persistent high cortisol responses to repeated psychological stress in a subpopulation of healthy men]. Psychosomat. Med. 57:468\u201374.</ref> This over-response of the central nervous system to stress therefore causes maladaptive chronic stress-like effects to memory processing systems.<ref name=\"Mizoguchi\"/>\n\n==Strategies==\n\n===Cognitive training===\nDiscovering that the brain can change as a result of experience has resulted in the development of [[Brain fitness|cognitive training]]. Cognitive training improves cognitive functioning, which can increase [[working memory]] capacity and improve [[Cognition|cognitive skills]] and functions in clinical populations with [[working memory]] deficiencies.<ref name=\"Morrison\">Morrison, AB., & Chein, JM. (2010). [http://www.highiqpro.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/Morrison_Chein2011.pdf Does working memory training work? the promise and challenges of enhancing cognition by training working memory]. Psychonomic Society, Inc.</ref>  Cognitive training may focus on [[attention]], [[Mental chronometry|speed of processing]], [[neurofeedback]], [[Dual-task paradigm|dual-tasking]] and [[Perception|perceptual]] training.<ref name=\"Morrison\"/>\n\nCognitive training has been shown to improve cognitive abilities for up to five years. In one experiment, the goal was to prove that cognitive training would increase the cognitive functions in older adults by using three types of training (memory, reasoning and speed of processing). It was found that improvements in cognitive ability not only was maintained over time but had a positive transfer effect on everyday functioning. Therefore, these results indicate that each type of cognitive training can produce immediate and lasting improvements in each kind of cognitive ability, thus suggesting that training can be beneficial to improving memory.<ref name=\"Willis\">Willis, SL., Tennstedt, SL., Marsiske, M., Ball, K., Elias, J., Koepke, KM., Morris, JN., Rebok, GW., Unverzagt, FW., Stoddard, AM., & Wright, E. (2006). [http://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/204643 Long-term effects of cognitive training on everyday functional outcomes in older adults]. National Institutes of Health, 296(23), 2805-2814.</ref>\n\nCognitive training in areas other than memory has actually been seen to generalize and transfer to memory systems. For example, the Improvement in Memory with Plasticity-based Adaptive Cognitive Training (IMPACT) study by the [[American Geriatrics Society]] in 2009 demonstrated that cognitive training designed to improve accuracy and speed of the [[auditory system]] presented improvements in memory and attention system functioning as well as auditory functioning.<ref>Smith, G.E., Housen, P., Yaffe, K., Ruff, R., Kennison, R.F., Mahncke, H.W., Zelinski, E.M. (2009). [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4169294/ A Cognitive Training Program Based on Principles of Brain Plasticity: Results from the Improvement in Memory with Plasticity-based Adaptive Cognitive Training (IMPACT) Study].  The American Geriatrics Society.</ref>\n[[File:Brain animated color nevit.gif|thumb|Human Brain]]\nTwo cognitive training methods are:\n\n* '''Strategy training''' is used to help individuals remember increasing amounts of information of a particular type. It involves teaching effective approaches to [[Encoding (memory)|encoding]], [[Working memory#Neural maintenance|maintenance]], and/or [[Recall (memory)|recall]] from working memory. The main goal of strategy training is to increase performance in tasks requiring retention of information. Studies strongly support the claim that the amount of information remembered can be increased by rehearsing out loud, telling a story with stimuli, or using imagery to make stimuli stand out. Strategy training has been used in children with [[Down syndrome]] and also in older adult populations.<ref name=\"Morrison\"/>\n* '''Core training''' involves repetition of demanding working memory tasks.  Some core training programs involve a combination of several tasks with widely varying stimulus types. The diversity of exercises increase the chance that one of, or some combination of the training tasks, will produce desired training-related gains. A goal of cognitive training is to impact the ease and success of cognitive performance in one's daily life. Core training can reduce the symptoms of [[attention deficit hyperactivity disorder]] (ADHD) and improve the quality of life involving patients with [[multiple sclerosis]], [[schizophrenia]] and also, those who have suffered from [[stroke]].<ref name=\"Morrison\"/>\n\nThe manner in which a training study is conducted could affect the outcomes or perspection of the outcomes. Expectancy/effort effects occur when the experimenter subconsciously influences the participants to perform a desired result. One form of [[expectancy bias]] relates to [[placebo]] effects, which is the belief that training should have a positive influence on cognition.  A [[Treatment group|control group]] may help to eliminate this bias because this group would not expect to benefit from the training.  Researchers sometimes generalize their results, which can be misleading and incorrect.  An example is to generalize findings of a single task and interpret the observed improvements as a broadly defined cognitive ability.  The study may result in inconsistency if there are a variety of comparison groups used in working memory training, which is impacted by: training and assessment timeline, assessment conditions, training setting and control group selection.<ref name=\"Morrison\"/>\n\nThe Five x Five System is a set of memory enhancement tools that are scientifically validated. The system was created by Dr Peter Marshall for research purposes at Royal Holloway, University of London. The system involves 5 groups of 5 tactics designed to maximise storage and recall at each stage of the process of registering, short-term storage, long-term storage, consolidation and retrieval and was designed to test efficacy of including memory training in school curricula.  Each section is of equal text length so that it can be taught verbatim in the same amount of time by all competent teachers.<ref>Marshall, P (2012) Improving Your Memory: The Unique 5 x 5 System, Bexley-on-Sea: Oakley Books {{ISBN|978-0-9569784-6-2}}</ref>\n\n=== Personal Application & Intellectual Conception ===\n'''[[Testing effect|Testing Effect]]''' is when most of the learning is allocated to declarative knowledge [[Long-term memory|long term memory]] is enhanced, this is otherwise known as the testing effect .<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Memory|last=Baddeley, Alan D., 1934-|date=2009|publisher=Psychology Press|others=Eysenck, Michael W., Anderson, Michael C. (Michael Christopher)|isbn=978-1-84872-000-8|location=Hove [England]|oclc=237880710}}</ref> In order to retrieve information from your memory you must practice doing it.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Small teaching : everyday lessons from the science of learning|last=Lang, James M.|date=cop. 2016|publisher=Jossey-Bass & Pfeiffer|isbn=978-1-118-94449-3|location=|pages=|oclc=955939138}}</ref>\u00a0 The more frequent practicing memorizing the more capable and likely you are to remember it later.<ref name=\":1\" /> The development of an effective retrieval structure that makes it easier to access information that has been stored in long-term memory is facilitated by using repeated retrieval practice.<ref name=\":0\" /> Testing effect occurs because of \u00a0the development of an adequate retrieval structure.<ref name=\":0\" /> The testing effect is different from re-reading because the information being learned is being practiced and tested which forces the information to be drawn from memory to recall.<ref name=\":1\" /> The testing effect allows for information to be recalled over a longer period as it is used as a self-testing tool and aids in having the ability to recall information in the future.<ref>{{Cite book|title=How memory works-and how to make it work for you|last=Madigan, Robert.|isbn=978-1-4625-2037-4|oclc=958867556|date = 2015-06-11}}</ref> This strategy is effective when using memory recall especially for information that is being tested on and needs to be in long-term memory.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''[[Concept map|Concept Maps]]''' \u201care diagrams that link word concepts in a fluid manner to central key concepts.\u201d <ref name=\":0\" /> They center around a main topic or idea, with lines protruding from the center with related information.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Budd|first=John W.|date=2010-08-07|title=Mind Maps As Classroom Exercises|url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.3200/JECE.35.1.35-46?casa_token=OCRi1dOlMK8AAAAA%3AF74M3Tmd1zOWWoUU4mP1qANKfwEFCnHaIWJYhHiC7jUI-4rc6JXtIPlq6uvtlU8A65JFQM1nnUQZ8A&|journal=The Journal of Economic Education|language=en|doi=10.3200/JECE.35.1.35-46}}</ref> Other concepts and ideas are then written at the end of each of the lines with new, related information. These related ideas are usually one or two words in length, giving only the essence of what is needed for [[memory retrieval]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Related ideas can also be drawn at the ends of the lines. This may be especially useful, given the drawing effect (people remember images better than words).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Childers|first=Terry L.|last2=Houston|first2=Michael J.|date=1984|title=Conditions for a Picture-Superiority Effect on Consumer Memory|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/2488971|journal=Journal of Consumer Research|volume=11|issue=2|pages=643\u2013654|issn=0093-5301}}</ref> These diagrams are beneficial because they require the creator to link and integrate different ideas, which improve critical thinking and leads to more meaningful learning.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=D'Antoni|first=Anthony V.|last2=Zipp|first2=Genevieve Pinto|last3=Olson|first3=Valerie G.|last4=Cahill|first4=Terrence F.|date=2010-09-16|title=Does the mind map learning strategy facilitate information retrieval and critical thinking in medical students?|url=https://doi.org/10.1186/1472-6920-10-61|journal=BMC Medical Education|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=61|doi=10.1186/1472-6920-10-61|issn=1472-6920|pmc=2949690|pmid=20846442}}</ref> Concept maps also help to facilitate the storage of material in long term memory, as well as help to show visually an knowledge gaps that may be present.<ref name=\":0\" /> Concept maps have been shown to improve people's ability to complete novel problem solving tasks.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Novak|first=Joseph D.|date=1990-01-01|title=Concept maps and Vee diagrams: two metacognitive tools to facilitate meaningful learning|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00377984|journal=Instructional Science|language=en|volume=19|issue=1|pages=29\u201352|doi=10.1007/BF00377984|issn=1573-1952}}</ref>\n\nThe Drawing Effect is another way to improve memory. Studies show that images are better remembered than words, something that is now known as the picture-superiority effect.<ref name=\":3\" /> Furthermore, another study found that when people are studying vocabulary, they remember more when they draw the definition, in comparison to writing it.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wammes|first=Jeffrey D.|last2=Meade|first2=Melissa E.|last3=Fernandes|first3=Myra A.|date=September 2017|title=Learning terms and definitions: Drawing and the role of elaborative encoding|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28756291|journal=Acta Psychologica|volume=179|pages=104\u2013113|doi=10.1016/j.actpsy.2017.07.008|issn=1873-6297|pmid=28756291}}</ref> This is thought to be because drawing uses 3 different types of memory- elaborative, motor, and pictorial.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Fernandes|first=Myra A.|last2=Wammes|first2=Jeffrey D.|last3=Meade|first3=Melissa E.|date=2018-10-01|title=The Surprisingly Powerful Influence of Drawing on Memory|url=https://doi.org/10.1177/0963721418755385|journal=Current Directions in Psychological Science|language=en|volume=27|issue=5|pages=302\u2013308|doi=10.1177/0963721418755385|issn=0963-7214}}</ref> The benefit of using pictures to enhance memory is even seen at an older age, including in dementia patients.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n'''Techniques to improving memory: visual memory'''\n\n[[Method of loci]] is a technique utilized for [[Recall (memory)|memory recall]] when to-be-remembered items are associated with different locations that are well known to the learner.<ref name=\":0\" /> Method of loci is one of the oldest and most effective mnemonics based on visual imagery.<ref name=\":0\" /> The more you exercise your visual memory through using objects to recall information better memory recall you will have.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Memory : what it is and how to improve it|last=Kay, David|date=1888|publisher=D. Appleton and Co|oclc=881360195}}</ref> The locations that are utilized when using the method of loci aids in the effectiveness of memory recall.<ref name=\":0\" /> For example, using the location of a driving route to work is more effective than using a room within a home because items in a room can be moved around while a route to work is more constant without items being moved around.<ref name=\":0\" /> There are limitations when using method of loci, it is difficult to recall any given item without working your way through the list sequence, which can be time consuming.<ref name=\":0\" /> Another limitation is that it is not useful when an individual is trying to learn and remember the real world.<ref name=\":0\" /> This [[Mnemonic|mnemonic technique]] plus others are effective because they allow the learner to apply their own knowledge to enhance their [[memory recall]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n----Is this a direct quote or paraphrase? [GU1]\n\nAlso don't forget to hyperlink\n\n===Psychopharmacology===\n{{Further|Nootropics}}\n[[Psychopharmacology]] is the scientific study of the actions of drugs and their effects on [[Mood (psychology)|mood]], [[Sense|sensation]], [[thought]], and [[behavior]].\n\nEvidence that aspects of memory can be improved by action on selective neurotransmitter systems, such as the [[cholinergic|cholinergic system]] which releases acetylcholine, has possible therapeutic benefits for patients with cognitive disorders.<ref name=\"Robbins2000\">{{cite journal|last1=Robbins|first1=T. W.|title=NEUROSCIENCE: Boosting Working Memory|journal=Science|volume=290|issue=5500|year=2000|pages=2275\u20132276|issn=0036-8075|doi=10.1126/science.290.5500.2275|pmid=11188728}}</ref>\n\nFindings from studies have indicated that acute administration of [[nicotine]] can improve cognitive performance (particularly tasks that require attention), short-term [[episodic memory]] and [[prospective memory]] task performance.  Chronic usage of low-dose nicotine in animals has been found to increase the number of [[Nicotinic acetylcholine receptor|neuronal nicotinic acetylcholine receptors]] (nAChRs) and improve performance on learning and memory tasks.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Heishman | first1 = S. J. | title = Meta-analysis of the acute effects of nicotine and smoking on human performance  | journal = Psychopharmacology | volume = 210 | issue = 4 | pages = 453\u2013469 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.1007/s00213-010-1848-1 | last2 = Kleykamp | first2 = B. A. | last3 = Singleton | first3 = E. G. | pmid=20414766 | pmc=3151730}}</ref>\n\nShort-term nicotine treatment, utilising nicotine skin patches, have shown that it may be possible to improve cognitive performance in a variety of groups such as normal non-smoking adults, Alzheimer's disease patients, [[Schizophrenia|schizophrenics]], and adults with [[attention deficit hyperactivity disorder|attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder]].<ref>Swan, G. E., & Lessov-Schlaggar, C. N. (2007). The effects of tobacco smoke and nicotine on cognition and the brain. Neuropsychol Rev, 17:259\u2013273.</ref> Similarly, evidence suggests that smoking improves visuospatial working memory impairments in schizophrenic patients, possibly explaining the high rate of tobacco smoking found in people with schizophrenia.<ref>Sacco, K. A., Termine, A., Seyal, A., Dudas, M. M., Vessicchio, J. C., Krishnan-Sarin, S., Jatlow, P. I., Bruce E. Wexler, B. E., & George, T. P. (2005). [http://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapsychiatry/fullarticle/208660 Effects of Cigarette Smoking on Spatial Working Memory and Attentional Deficits in Schizophrenia]. ARCH GEN PSYCHIATRY, 62, 659\u2013659.</ref>\n\n===Diet===\n[[File:Milch-Jogurt-Fr\u00fcchte.jpg|thumb|Healthy fruits and vegetables]]\n\nThere is some evidence glucose consumption may have a positive impact on memory performance, though not in young adults.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Korol DL |title=Enhancing cognitive function across the life span |journal=Ann. N. Y. Acad. Sci. |volume=959 |issue= |pages=167\u201379 |year=2002 |pmid=11976194 |type=Review |doi=10.1111/j.1749-6632.2002.tb02091.x}}</ref>\n\n===Stress management===\n[[File:Trataka.JPG|thumb|150px|Meditation:attending to a flame]]\n[[Meditation]], a form of mental training to focus attention,<ref name=\"Slagter\"/> has been shown to increase the control over brain resource distribution, improving both [[attention]] and [[self control|self-regulation]].<ref name=\"Tang\"/> The changes are potentially long-lasting as meditation may have the ability to strengthen neuronal circuits as selective attentional processes improve.<ref name=\"Xiong\">Xiong, G.L. and Doraiswamy, M. (2009).  [http://dl.dropbox.com/u/5317066/2009-xiong.pdf \"Does Meditation Enhance Cognition and Brain Plasticity?\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201042156/http://dl.dropbox.com/u/5317066/2009-xiong.pdf |date=2012-02-01 }} ''Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences''. Vol 1172, pages 63-69.</ref>  Meditation may also enhance [[LC4MP|cognitive limited capacity]], affecting the way in which stimuli are processed.<ref name=\"Slagter\"/>\n\nMeditation practice has also been associated with physical changes in brain structure. [[Magnetic resonance imaging]] (MRI) of Buddhist insight meditation practitioners who practiced [[Mindfulness (Buddhism)|mindfulness]] meditation were found to have an increase in cortical thickness  and hippocampus volume compared to the control group.<ref>Luders, E., Toga, A.W., Lepore, N., Gaser, C. (2009). [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3184843/ The underlying anatomical correlates of long-term meditation: Larger hippocampal and frontal volumes of gray matter]. NeuroImage Volume 45, Issue 3. Pages 672-678.</ref>  This research provides structural evidence that meditation practice promotes neural plasticity and experience-dependent cortical plasticity.<ref>Lazar, S.W., Kerr, C.E., Wasserman, R.H., et al. (2005). [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1361002/ Meditation experience is associated with increased cortical thickness]. NeuroReport. Vol 16(17) 1893\u20131897.</ref>\n\n===Exercise===\n{{main|Neurobiological effects of physical exercise#Long-term effects}}\nIn both human and animal studies, [[Physical exercise|exercise]] has been shown to improve cognitive performance on encoding and retrieval tasks. [[Morris water navigation task|Morris water maze]] and radial arm water maze studies of [[rodent]]s found that, when compared to [[Sedentary lifestyle|sedentary]] animals, exercised mice showed improved performance traversing the water maze and displayed enhanced memory for the location of an escape platform.<ref name=\"Berchtold\">Berchtold, N. C., Castello, N., & Cotman, C. W. (2010). [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2857396/ Exercise and time-dependent benefits to learning and memory]. ''Neuroscience'' 167, 588\u2013597.</ref> Likewise, human studies have shown that cognitive performance is improved due to [[Human physiology|physiological]] arousal, which speeded mental processes and enhanced memory storage and retrieval.<ref>Lambourne, K., & Tomporowski, P. (2010). The effect of exercise-induced arousal on cognitive task performance: A meta-regression analysis. Brainresearch, 1341, 1 2 \u2013 2 4.</ref>  Ongoing exercise interventions have been found to favourably impact memory processes in older adults<ref>Colcombe, S. J., Kramer, A. F. (2003). [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Arthur_Kramer2/publication/10833611_Fitness_Effects_on_the_Cognitive_Function_of_Older_Adults_A_Meta-Analytic_Study/links/0fcfd50da2a5b0ae48000000/Fitness-Effects-on-the-Cognitive-Function-of-Older-Adults-A-Meta-Analytic-Study.pdf Fitness effects on the cognitive function of older adults: a meta-analytic study]. ''Psychol. Sci''. 14, 125\u2013130.</ref> and children.<ref>Hillman, C .H., Castelli, D. M., Buck, S. M. (2005). [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Darla_Castelli/publication/7481314_Aerobic_Fitness_and_Neurocognitive_Function_in_Healthy_Preadolescent_Children/links/0fcfd50aa31f620049000000.pdf Aerobic fitness and neurocognitive function in healthy preadolescent children]. ''Med. Sci. Sports Exerc.'' 37, 1967\u20131974.</ref>\n\nExercise has been found to positively regulate [[hippocampus|hippocampal]] [[neurogenesis]],<ref>van Praag H, Kempermann G, Gage FH. 1999b. [http://www.rg-40.com/Running_Increases.htm Running increases cell proliferation and neurogenesis in the adult mouse dentate gyrus]. Nat Neurosci 2:266\u2013270.</ref> which is considered an explanation for the positive influence of physical activities on memory performance. Hippocampus-dependent learning, for example, can promote the survival of newborn neurons which may serve as a foundation for the formation of new memories.<ref>Van der Borght, K., Havekes, R., Bos, T., Eggen, B. J., & Van der Zee, E. A. (2007). [https://www.rug.nl/research/portal/files/3623253/2007BehavNeuroscivdBorght.pdf Exercise Improves Memory Acquisition and Retrieval in the Y-Maze Task: Relationship With Hippocampal Neurogenesis]. ''Behavioral Neuroscience'', 121 (2), 324\u2013334.</ref>  Exercise has been found to increase the level of [[brain-derived neurotrophic factor]] (BDNF) protein in rats, with elevated BDNF levels corresponding with strengthened performance on memory tasks. Data also suggests that BDNF availability at the beginning of [[cognitive test]]ing is related to the overall acquisition of a new cognitive task and may be important in determining the strength of recall in memory tasks.<ref name=\"Berchtold\"/>\n\nHence, brain exercises are found being practiced and adopted early by children to [https://brainy.co.in/sensory-enhancement enhance brain sensory responses] and improve performance of the brain by maintaining its health.\n\nA meta-analysis concluded that specifically [[resistance training]], as compared to cardiovascular exercise, had no measurable effect on working memory.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Landrigan JF, Bell T, Crowe M, Clay OJ, Mirman D |title=Lifting cognition: a meta-analysis of effects of resistance exercise on cognition |journal=Psychol Res |volume= |issue= |pages= |date=2019 |pmid=30627769 |doi=10.1007/s00426-019-01145-x |url=https://www.pure.ed.ac.uk/ws/files/121873388/exercise_accepted_ms_1_.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Mental exercise===\n[[Aristotle]] wrote a [[treatise]] about memory: ''[[On memory|De memoria et reminiscentia]]''.  To improve recollection, he advised that a systematic search should be made and that practice was helpful.  He suggested grouping the items to be remembered in threes and then concentrating upon the central member of each triad (group of three).<ref name=Anne>{{citation |title=Memory |author=Anne Whitehead |chapter=Memory and Inscription |pages=15\u201349}}</ref>\n\nMusic playing has recently gained attention as a possible way to promote brain plasticity. Promising results have been found suggesting that learning music can improve various aspects of memory. For instance, children who participated in one year of instrumental musical training showed improved verbal memory, whereas no such improvement was shown in children who discontinued musical training.<ref>Wan, C. Y., & Schlaug, G. (2010). [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2996135/?c=029 Music making as a tool for promoting brain plasticity across the life span]. The Neuroscientist, 16(5), 566\u2013 577.</ref> Similarly, adults with no previous musical training who participated in individualized piano instruction showed significantly improved performance on tasks designed to test attention and working memory compared to a healthy control group.<ref>Bugos, J. A.,  Perlstein, W. M., McCrae, C. S., Brophy, T. S., & Bedenbaugh, P. H. (2007). [http://upperhandspiano.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Piano-Lessons-Increase-Executive-Function-and-Memory-.pdf Individualized Piano Instruction enhances executive functioning and working memory in older adults]. Aging & Mental Health, 11(4): 464\u2013471.</ref> Evidence suggests that the improvements to verbal, working and long-term memory associated to musical training are a result of the enhanced verbal rehearsal mechanisms musicians possess.<ref>Franklin, M. S., Moore, K., Yip, C., Jonides, J., Rattray, K., & Moher, J. (2008). [http://tanclab.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/7_POM_Franklin_etal2008.pdf The effects of musical training on verbal memory]. Psychology of Music, 36(3), 353 \u2013 365.</ref>\n\nAnother study tested elderly participants in how learning a new activity impacts their memory and mental control.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Park|first=Denise C.|last2=Lodi-Smith|first2=Jennifer|last3=Drew|first3=Linda|last4=Haber|first4=Sara|last5=Hebrank|first5=Andrew|last6=Bischof|first6=G\u00e9rard N.|last7=Aamodt|first7=Whitley|date=January 2014|title=The Impact of Sustained Engagement on Cognitive Function in Older Adults: The Synapse Project|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4154531/|journal=Psychological science|volume=25|issue=1|pages=103\u2013112|doi=10.1177/0956797613499592|issn=0956-7976|pmc=4154531|pmid=24214244}}</ref> They were divided into 5 groups that each spent 15 hours a week doing one of 5 different scenarios: learning digital photography, learning to quilt, learning both digital photography and how to quilt, socializing with others, or doing solitary activities by themselves. It was found that all groups improved with regard to mental control, however learning a new skill(s) lead to improved episodic memory.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cognitive enhancer]]\n*[[Effect of caffeine on memory]]\n*[[Emotion and memory]]\n*[[Music-related memory]]\n*[[Sleep and Memory]]\n*[[Spaced repetition]]\n*[[Working memory training]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Memory}}\n\n[[Category:Memory processes]]\n[[Category:Neuroscience]]\n", "text_old": "{{more medical citations needed|date=August 2015}}\n[[File:Hippocampus small.gif|thumb|The hippocampus regulates memory function.]]\n'''Memory improvement''' is the act of improving one's memory. Memory deficits, age-related memory loss, and people's want to improve their own memory has lead to research on how to best help people to improve their memory. Research has also worked to determine what factors influence memory and cognition. Many different techniques to improve memory have been found, including [[cognitive training]], [[Psychopharmacology|psychopharmacology,]] [[diet]], [[stress management]], and [[exercise]]. Each technique has the ability to influence memory in a different ways. [[Neuroimaging]] has also provided [[Neuroscience|neurobiological]] evidence supporting [[Holism|holistic]] ways in which one can improve memory.\n\n==Memory function factors==\n\n=== Neuroplasticity===\n[[Neuroplasticity]] is the mechanism by which the brain encodes experience, learns new behaviours and relearns lost behaviour if the brain has been damaged.<ref name=\"Kleim\">Kleim, JA., & Jones, TA. (2008). [http://www.bridgesnky.org/uploads/2016_Experience-Dependent_Neuroplasticity.pdf Principles of experience-dependent neural plasticity: implications for rehabilitation after brain damage]. Journal of Speech, Language, and Hearing Research, 51, S225-S239.</ref>\n\n[[File:Hackney carriage.jpg|thumb|London Taxicab]]Experience-dependent neuroplasticity suggests that the brain changes in response to what it experiences. [[London]] [[taxicab]] drivers provide a great example of this dynamic. They undergo extensive training for 2\u20134 years, learning and memorizing street names, layout of streets within the city and the quickest cross-city routes.  After studying London taxicab drivers over a period of time, it was found that the [[grey matter]] volume increased over time in the posterior [[hippocampus]], an area in the brain involved heavily in memory. The longer taxi drivers navigated the streets of London, the greater the posterior hippocampal gray matter volume.  This suggests a correlation between a healthy person's mental training or exercise and their brains capacity to manage greater volume and more complex information. The increase in volume actually led to a decrease in the taxi drivers' ability to acquire new visuo-spatial information.<ref name=\"Maguire\">Maguire, EA., Woollett, K., & Spiers, HJ. (2006). [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Hugo_Spiers/publication/6769737_London_Taxi_Drivers_and_Bus_Drivers_A_Structural_MRI_and_Neuropsychological_Analysis/links/09e41508a947d83c7a000000.pdf London taxi drivers and bus drivers]: a structural MRI and neuropsychological analysis. ''Hippocampus'', 16, 1091-1101.</ref>\n\n===Stress===\nResearch has found that chronic and acute stress have adverse effects on memory processing systems. Therefore, it is important to find mechanisms in which one can reduce the amount of stress in their lives when seeking to improve memory.\n\n* '''[[Chronic stress]]''' has been shown to have negative impacts on the brain, especially in [[Memory#Processes|memory processing]] systems.<ref name=\"Mizoguchi\">Mizoguchi, K., Mitsutoshi, Y., Ishige, A., et al. (2000). [http://www.jneurosci.org/content/20/4/1568.long Chronic Stress Induces Impairment of Spatial Working Memory Because of Prefrontal Dopaminergic Dysfunction]. The Journal of Neuroscience Vol 20(4) 1568-1574.</ref> The hippocampus is vulnerable to repeated stress due to adrenal steroid stress hormones.<ref>Jacobson, L. & Sapolsky, R.M. [http://press.endocrine.org/doi/pdf/10.1210/edrv-12-2-118 The role of the hippocampus in feedback regulation of the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis]. Endo. Rev. 12, 118\u2212134 (1991).</ref>  Elevated [[glucocorticoids]], a class of [[Adrenal cortex|adrenal]] [[steroid hormone]]s, results in increased [[cortisol]], a well known stress response hormone in the brain,<ref>Starkman, M. N., Gebarski, S. S., Berent, S. & Schteingart, D. E. (1992). [https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/handle/2027.42/29769/0000107.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y Hippocampal formation volume, memory dysfunction, and cortisol levels in patients with Cushing's syndrome]. ''Biol. Psychiatry'' 32, 756\u2212765.</ref> and glucocorticoids are known to affect memory.<ref name=\"McEwen\">McEwen, B.S. (1999). [https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/ed19/1283e8be2c70a4f9aa0bc87eb6f51f33b99d.pdf Stress and Hippocampal Plasticity]. Annual Review of Neuroscience. Vol. 22: 105-122.</ref> Prolonged high cortisol levels, as seen in chronic stress, have been shown to result in reduced hippocampal volume as well as deficits in hippocampal-dependent memory, as seen in impaired [[Declarative memory|declarative]], [[Episodic memory|episodic]], [[Spatial memory|spatial]], and [[Context-dependent memory|contextual]] memory performance.<ref name=\"McEwen\"/>  Chronic, long-term high cortisol levels affect the degree of hippocampal atrophy, resulting in as much as a 14% hippocampal volume reduction and impaired hippocampus-dependent memory when compared to elderly subjects with decreased or moderate cortisol levels.<ref name=\"McEwen\"/><ref>Squire, L. R. (1992). [http://whoville.ucsd.edu/PDFs/188_Squire_PsychRev_1992.pdf Memory and the hippocampus : A synthesis from findings with rats, monkeys, and humans]. Psychol. Rev. 99, 195\u2212231.</ref><ref name=\"Sapolsky\">Sapolsky, R. M., Krey, L. C. & McEwen, B. S. (2002) The neuroendocrinology of stress and aging: The glucocorticoid cascade hypothesis. Endo. Rev. 7, 284\u2212301.</ref> An example ''may'' be found in the London taxi drivers, as the anterior hippocampus was hypothesized to decrease in volume as a result of elevated cortisol levels from stress.<ref name=\"Maguire\"/>{{#tag:ref|Quote from Maguire: \"Increases in plasma or salivary cortisol are often used as a biochemical marker of stress. Elevated cortisol levels have been associated with poor performance on memory tasks (Newcomer et al., 1999; Cho et al., 2000) and reduced hippocampal volume (Lupien et al., 1998). Thus, stress may have induced the anterior hippocampal volume reduction in the taxi drivers.\"<ref name=\"Maguire\"/>|group=\"nb\"}}\n* '''[[Fight-or-flight response|Acute stress]],''' a more common form of stress, results in the release of adrenal steroids resulting in impaired short-term and working memory processes such as [[selective attention]], [[memory consolidation]], as well as long-term potentiation.<ref>Lupien SJ, McEwen BS. 1997. The acute effects of corticosteroids on cognition: integration of animal and human model studies. Brain Res. Rev. 24:1\u201327.</ref><ref>McEwen, B.S. (1998). [https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/ee3c/1a87d21b1865abe72157226e38103b0d95cf.pdf Protective and damaging effects of stress mediators]. New Engl. J. Med. 238, 171\u2212179.</ref>  The human brain has a limited [[short-term memory]] capacity to process information, which results in constant competition between stimuli to become processed. [[Executive functions|Cognitive control]] processes such as selective attention reduce this competition by prioritizing where attentional resources are distributed.  Attention is crucial in memory processing and enhances encoding and strength of memory traces.<ref name=\"Shiffrin\">Shiffrin, R.M. (1976). Capacity limitations in information processing, attention, and memory. In W.K. Estes (Ed.), Handbook of learning and cognitive processes (Vol. 4). Hillsdale, NJ: Erlbaum.</ref> It is therefore important to selectively attend to relevant information and ignore irrelevant information in order to have the greatest success at remembering.<ref name=\"Slagter\">Slagter, H.A., Lutz, A., Greischar, L.L., Francis, A.D., Nieuwenhuis, S., Davis, J.M., Davidson, R.J. (2007). [http://journals.plos.org/plosbiology/article?id=10.1371/journal.pbio.0050138 Mental Training Affects Distribution of Limited Brain Resources].  PLoS Biol Vol 5(6).</ref>\n\n:Animal and human studies provide evidence as they report that acute stress impairs the maintenance of [[short-term memory]] and [[working memory]] and aggravates [[Neuropsychiatry|neuropsychiatric]] disorders involved in short-term and working memory such as [[Depression (mood)|depression]] and [[schizophrenia]].<ref name=\"Mizoguchi\"/> Animal studies with rats have also shown that exposure to acute stress reduces the survival of hippocampal neurons.<ref name=\"Tang\">Tang, Y.Y., Ma, Y. Wang, Y., Fan, Y. Et al. (2007). [http://www.pnas.org/content/104/43/17152.full Short-term meditation training improves attention and self-regulation]. PNAS. vol. 104 no. 43 17152-17156.</ref>\n\n:One of the roles of the [[central nervous system]] (CNS) is to help adapt to stressful environments.<ref name=\"Mizoguchi\"/> It has been suggested that acute stress may have a protective function for individuals more vulnerable to their own stress hormones. Some individuals, for example, are not able to decrease or habituate their cortisol elevation, which plays a major role in hippocampal atrophy.<ref>Kirschbaum C, Prussner JC, Stone AA, Federenko I, Gaab J. 1995. [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Clemens_Kirschbaum/publication/14647264_Kirschbaum_C_Prussner_JC_Stone_AA_Federenko_I_Gaab_J_Lintz_D_Schommer_N_Hellhammer_DH._Persistent_high_cortisol_responses_to_repeated_psychological_stress_in_a_subpopulation_of_healthy_men/links/0912f50f7b25435a39000000.pdf Persistent high cortisol responses to repeated psychological stress in a subpopulation of healthy men]. Psychosomat. Med. 57:468\u201374.</ref> This over-response of the central nervous system to stress therefore causes maladaptive chronic stress-like effects to memory processing systems.<ref name=\"Mizoguchi\"/>\n\n==Strategies==\n\n===Cognitive training===\nDiscovering that the brain can change as a result of experience has resulted in the development of [[Brain fitness|cognitive training]]. Cognitive training improves cognitive functioning, which can increase [[working memory]] capacity and improve [[Cognition|cognitive skills]] and functions in clinical populations with [[working memory]] deficiencies.<ref name=\"Morrison\">Morrison, AB., & Chein, JM. (2010). [http://www.highiqpro.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/Morrison_Chein2011.pdf Does working memory training work? the promise and challenges of enhancing cognition by training working memory]. Psychonomic Society, Inc.</ref>  Cognitive training may focus on [[attention]], [[Mental chronometry|speed of processing]], [[neurofeedback]], [[Dual-task paradigm|dual-tasking]] and [[Perception|perceptual]] training.<ref name=\"Morrison\"/>\n\nCognitive training has been shown to improve cognitive abilities for up to five years. In one experiment, the goal was to prove that cognitive training would increase the cognitive functions in older adults by using three types of training (memory, reasoning and speed of processing). It was found that improvements in cognitive ability not only was maintained over time but had a positive transfer effect on everyday functioning. Therefore, these results indicate that each type of cognitive training can produce immediate and lasting improvements in each kind of cognitive ability, thus suggesting that training can be beneficial to improving memory.<ref name=\"Willis\">Willis, SL., Tennstedt, SL., Marsiske, M., Ball, K., Elias, J., Koepke, KM., Morris, JN., Rebok, GW., Unverzagt, FW., Stoddard, AM., & Wright, E. (2006). [http://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/204643 Long-term effects of cognitive training on everyday functional outcomes in older adults]. National Institutes of Health, 296(23), 2805-2814.</ref>\n\nCognitive training in areas other than memory has actually been seen to generalize and transfer to memory systems. For example, the Improvement in Memory with Plasticity-based Adaptive Cognitive Training (IMPACT) study by the [[American Geriatrics Society]] in 2009 demonstrated that cognitive training designed to improve accuracy and speed of the [[auditory system]] presented improvements in memory and attention system functioning as well as auditory functioning.<ref>Smith, G.E., Housen, P., Yaffe, K., Ruff, R., Kennison, R.F., Mahncke, H.W., Zelinski, E.M. (2009). [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4169294/ A Cognitive Training Program Based on Principles of Brain Plasticity: Results from the Improvement in Memory with Plasticity-based Adaptive Cognitive Training (IMPACT) Study].  The American Geriatrics Society.</ref>\n[[File:Brain animated color nevit.gif|thumb|Human Brain]]\nTwo cognitive training methods are:\n\n* '''Strategy training''' is used to help individuals remember increasing amounts of information of a particular type. It involves teaching effective approaches to [[Encoding (memory)|encoding]], [[Working memory#Neural maintenance|maintenance]], and/or [[Recall (memory)|recall]] from working memory. The main goal of strategy training is to increase performance in tasks requiring retention of information. Studies strongly support the claim that the amount of information remembered can be increased by rehearsing out loud, telling a story with stimuli, or using imagery to make stimuli stand out. Strategy training has been used in children with [[Down syndrome]] and also in older adult populations.<ref name=\"Morrison\"/>\n* '''Core training''' involves repetition of demanding working memory tasks.  Some core training programs involve a combination of several tasks with widely varying stimulus types. The diversity of exercises increase the chance that one of, or some combination of the training tasks, will produce desired training-related gains. A goal of cognitive training is to impact the ease and success of cognitive performance in one's daily life. Core training can reduce the symptoms of [[attention deficit hyperactivity disorder]] (ADHD) and improve the quality of life involving patients with [[multiple sclerosis]], [[schizophrenia]] and also, those who have suffered from [[stroke]].<ref name=\"Morrison\"/>\n\nThe manner in which a training study is conducted could affect the outcomes or perspection of the outcomes. Expectancy/effort effects occur when the experimenter subconsciously influences the participants to perform a desired result. One form of [[expectancy bias]] relates to [[placebo]] effects, which is the belief that training should have a positive influence on cognition.  A [[Treatment group|control group]] may help to eliminate this bias because this group would not expect to benefit from the training.  Researchers sometimes generalize their results, which can be misleading and incorrect.  An example is to generalize findings of a single task and interpret the observed improvements as a broadly defined cognitive ability.  The study may result in inconsistency if there are a variety of comparison groups used in working memory training, which is impacted by: training and assessment timeline, assessment conditions, training setting and control group selection.<ref name=\"Morrison\"/>\n\nThe Five x Five System is a set of memory enhancement tools that are scientifically validated. The system was created by Dr Peter Marshall for research purposes at Royal Holloway, University of London. The system involves 5 groups of 5 tactics designed to maximise storage and recall at each stage of the process of registering, short-term storage, long-term storage, consolidation and retrieval and was designed to test efficacy of including memory training in school curricula.  Each section is of equal text length so that it can be taught verbatim in the same amount of time by all competent teachers.<ref>Marshall, P (2012) Improving Your Memory: The Unique 5 x 5 System, Bexley-on-Sea: Oakley Books {{ISBN|978-0-9569784-6-2}}</ref>\n\n=== Personal Application & Intellectual Conception ===\n'''[[Testing effect|Testing Effect]]''' is when most of the learning is allocated to declarative knowledge [[Long-term memory|long term memory]] is enhanced, this is otherwise known as the testing effect .<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Memory|last=Baddeley, Alan D., 1934-|date=2009|publisher=Psychology Press|others=Eysenck, Michael W., Anderson, Michael C. (Michael Christopher)|isbn=978-1-84872-000-8|location=Hove [England]|oclc=237880710}}</ref> In order to retrieve information from your memory you must practice doing it.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Small teaching : everyday lessons from the science of learning|last=Lang, James M.|date=cop. 2016|publisher=Jossey-Bass & Pfeiffer|isbn=978-1-118-94449-3|location=|pages=|oclc=955939138}}</ref>\u00a0 The more frequent practicing memorizing the more capable and likely you are to remember it later.<ref name=\":1\" /> The development of an effective retrieval structure that makes it easier to access information that has been stored in long-term memory is facilitated by using repeated retrieval practice.<ref name=\":0\" /> Testing effect occurs because of \u00a0the development of an adequate retrieval structure.<ref name=\":0\" /> The testing effect is different from re-reading because the information being learned is being practiced and tested which forces the information to be drawn from memory to recall.<ref name=\":1\" /> The testing effect allows for information to be recalled over a longer period as it is used as a self-testing tool and aids in having the ability to recall information in the future.<ref>{{Cite book|title=How memory works-and how to make it work for you|last=Madigan, Robert.|isbn=978-1-4625-2037-4|oclc=958867556|date = 2015-06-11}}</ref> This strategy is effective when using memory recall especially for information that is being tested on and needs to be in long-term memory.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n'''[[Concept map|Concept Maps]]''' \u201care diagrams that link word concepts in a fluid manner to central key concepts.\u201d <ref name=\":0\" /> They center around a main topic or idea, with lines protruding from the center with related information.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Budd|first=John W.|date=2010-08-07|title=Mind Maps As Classroom Exercises|url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.3200/JECE.35.1.35-46?casa_token=OCRi1dOlMK8AAAAA%3AF74M3Tmd1zOWWoUU4mP1qANKfwEFCnHaIWJYhHiC7jUI-4rc6JXtIPlq6uvtlU8A65JFQM1nnUQZ8A&|journal=The Journal of Economic Education|language=en|doi=10.3200/JECE.35.1.35-46}}</ref> Other concepts and ideas are then written at the end of each of the lines with new, related information. These related ideas are usually one or two words in length, giving only the essence of what is needed for [[memory retrieval]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Related ideas can also be drawn at the ends of the lines. This may be especially useful, given the drawing effect (people remember images better than words).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Childers|first=Terry L.|last2=Houston|first2=Michael J.|date=1984|title=Conditions for a Picture-Superiority Effect on Consumer Memory|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/2488971|journal=Journal of Consumer Research|volume=11|issue=2|pages=643\u2013654|issn=0093-5301}}</ref> These diagrams are beneficial because they require the creator to link and integrate different ideas, which improve critical thinking and leads to more meaningful learning.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=D'Antoni|first=Anthony V.|last2=Zipp|first2=Genevieve Pinto|last3=Olson|first3=Valerie G.|last4=Cahill|first4=Terrence F.|date=2010-09-16|title=Does the mind map learning strategy facilitate information retrieval and critical thinking in medical students?|url=https://doi.org/10.1186/1472-6920-10-61|journal=BMC Medical Education|language=en|volume=10|issue=1|pages=61|doi=10.1186/1472-6920-10-61|issn=1472-6920|pmc=2949690|pmid=20846442}}</ref> Concept maps also help to facilitate the storage of material in long term memory, as well as help to show visually an knowledge gaps that may be present.<ref name=\":0\" /> Concept maps have been shown to improve people's ability to complete novel problem solving tasks.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Novak|first=Joseph D.|date=1990-01-01|title=Concept maps and Vee diagrams: two metacognitive tools to facilitate meaningful learning|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00377984|journal=Instructional Science|language=en|volume=19|issue=1|pages=29\u201352|doi=10.1007/BF00377984|issn=1573-1952}}</ref>\n\nThe Drawing Effect is another way to improve memory. Studies show that images are better remembered than words, something that is now known as the picture-superiority effect.<ref name=\":3\" /> Furthermore, another study found that when people are studying vocabulary, they remember more when they draw the definition, in comparison to writing it.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wammes|first=Jeffrey D.|last2=Meade|first2=Melissa E.|last3=Fernandes|first3=Myra A.|date=September 2017|title=Learning terms and definitions: Drawing and the role of elaborative encoding|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28756291|journal=Acta Psychologica|volume=179|pages=104\u2013113|doi=10.1016/j.actpsy.2017.07.008|issn=1873-6297|pmid=28756291}}</ref> This is thought to be because drawing uses 3 different types of memory- elaborative, motor, and pictorial.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Fernandes|first=Myra A.|last2=Wammes|first2=Jeffrey D.|last3=Meade|first3=Melissa E.|date=2018-10-01|title=The Surprisingly Powerful Influence of Drawing on Memory|url=https://doi.org/10.1177/0963721418755385|journal=Current Directions in Psychological Science|language=en|volume=27|issue=5|pages=302\u2013308|doi=10.1177/0963721418755385|issn=0963-7214}}</ref> The benefit of using pictures to enhance memory is even seen at an older age, including in dementia patients.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n'''Techniques to improving memory: visual memory'''\n\n[[Method of loci]] is a technique utilized for [[Recall (memory)|memory recall]] when to-be-remembered items are associated with different locations that are well known to the learner.<ref name=\":0\" /> Method of loci is one of the oldest and most effective mnemonics based on visual imagery.<ref name=\":0\" /> The more you exercise your visual memory through using objects to recall information better memory recall you will have.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Memory : what it is and how to improve it|last=Kay, David|date=1888|publisher=D. Appleton and Co|oclc=881360195}}</ref> The locations that are utilized when using the method of loci aids in the effectiveness of memory recall.<ref name=\":0\" /> For example, using the location of a driving route to work is more effective than using a room within a home because items in a room can be moved around while a route to work is more constant without items being moved around.<ref name=\":0\" /> There are limitations when using method of loci, it is difficult to recall any given item without working your way through the list sequence, which can be time consuming.<ref name=\":0\" /> Another limitation is that it is not useful when an individual is trying to learn and remember the real world.<ref name=\":0\" /> This [[Mnemonic|mnemonic technique]] plus others are effective because they allow the learner to apply their own knowledge to enhance their [[memory recall]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n----Is this a direct quote or paraphrase? [GU1]\n\nAlso don't forget to hyperlink\n\n===Psychopharmacology===\n{{Further|Nootropics}}\n[[Psychopharmacology]] is the scientific study of the actions of drugs and their effects on [[Mood (psychology)|mood]], [[Sense|sensation]], [[thought]], and [[behavior]].\n\nEvidence that aspects of memory can be improved by action on selective neurotransmitter systems, such as the [[cholinergic|cholinergic system]] which releases acetylcholine, has possible therapeutic benefits for patients with cognitive disorders.<ref name=\"Robbins2000\">{{cite journal|last1=Robbins|first1=T. W.|title=NEUROSCIENCE: Boosting Working Memory|journal=Science|volume=290|issue=5500|year=2000|pages=2275\u20132276|issn=0036-8075|doi=10.1126/science.290.5500.2275|pmid=11188728}}</ref>\n\nFindings from studies have indicated that acute administration of [[nicotine]] can improve cognitive performance (particularly tasks that require attention), short-term [[episodic memory]] and [[prospective memory]] task performance.  Chronic usage of low-dose nicotine in animals has been found to increase the number of [[Nicotinic acetylcholine receptor|neuronal nicotinic acetylcholine receptors]] (nAChRs) and improve performance on learning and memory tasks.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Heishman | first1 = S. J. | title = Meta-analysis of the acute effects of nicotine and smoking on human performance  | journal = Psychopharmacology | volume = 210 | issue = 4 | pages = 453\u2013469 | year = 2010 | doi = 10.1007/s00213-010-1848-1 | last2 = Kleykamp | first2 = B. A. | last3 = Singleton | first3 = E. G. | pmid=20414766 | pmc=3151730}}</ref>\n\nShort-term nicotine treatment, utilising nicotine skin patches, have shown that it may be possible to improve cognitive performance in a variety of groups such as normal non-smoking adults, Alzheimer's disease patients, [[Schizophrenia|schizophrenics]], and adults with [[attention deficit hyperactivity disorder|attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder]].<ref>Swan, G. E., & Lessov-Schlaggar, C. N. (2007). The effects of tobacco smoke and nicotine on cognition and the brain. Neuropsychol Rev, 17:259\u2013273.</ref> Similarly, evidence suggests that smoking improves visuospatial working memory impairments in schizophrenic patients, possibly explaining the high rate of tobacco smoking found in people with schizophrenia.<ref>Sacco, K. A., Termine, A., Seyal, A., Dudas, M. M., Vessicchio, J. C., Krishnan-Sarin, S., Jatlow, P. I., Bruce E. Wexler, B. E., & George, T. P. (2005). [http://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapsychiatry/fullarticle/208660 Effects of Cigarette Smoking on Spatial Working Memory and Attentional Deficits in Schizophrenia]. ARCH GEN PSYCHIATRY, 62, 659\u2013659.</ref>\n\n===Diet===\n[[File:Milch-Jogurt-Fr\u00fcchte.jpg|thumb|Healthy fruits and vegetables]]\n\nThere is some evidence glucose consumption may have a positive impact on memory performance, though not in young adults.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Korol DL |title=Enhancing cognitive function across the life span |journal=Ann. N. Y. Acad. Sci. |volume=959 |issue= |pages=167\u201379 |year=2002 |pmid=11976194 |type=Review |doi=10.1111/j.1749-6632.2002.tb02091.x}}</ref>\n\n===Stress management===\n[[File:Trataka.JPG|thumb|150px|Meditation:attending to a flame]]\n[[Meditation]], a form of mental training to focus attention,<ref name=\"Slagter\"/> has been shown to increase the control over brain resource distribution, improving both [[attention]] and [[self control|self-regulation]].<ref name=\"Tang\"/> The changes are potentially long-lasting as meditation may have the ability to strengthen neuronal circuits as selective attentional processes improve.<ref name=\"Xiong\">Xiong, G.L. and Doraiswamy, M. (2009).  [http://dl.dropbox.com/u/5317066/2009-xiong.pdf \"Does Meditation Enhance Cognition and Brain Plasticity?\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201042156/http://dl.dropbox.com/u/5317066/2009-xiong.pdf |date=2012-02-01 }} ''Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences''. Vol 1172, pages 63-69.</ref>  Meditation may also enhance [[LC4MP|cognitive limited capacity]], affecting the way in which stimuli are processed.<ref name=\"Slagter\"/>\n\nMeditation practice has also been associated with physical changes in brain structure. [[Magnetic resonance imaging]] (MRI) of Buddhist insight meditation practitioners who practiced [[Mindfulness (Buddhism)|mindfulness]] meditation were found to have an increase in cortical thickness  and hippocampus volume compared to the control group.<ref>Luders, E., Toga, A.W., Lepore, N., Gaser, C. (2009). [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3184843/ The underlying anatomical correlates of long-term meditation: Larger hippocampal and frontal volumes of gray matter]. NeuroImage Volume 45, Issue 3. Pages 672-678.</ref>  This research provides structural evidence that meditation practice promotes neural plasticity and experience-dependent cortical plasticity.<ref>Lazar, S.W., Kerr, C.E., Wasserman, R.H., et al. (2005). [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1361002/ Meditation experience is associated with increased cortical thickness]. NeuroReport. Vol 16(17) 1893\u20131897.</ref>\n\n===Exercise===\n{{main|Neurobiological effects of physical exercise#Long-term effects}}\nIn both human and animal studies, [[Physical exercise|exercise]] has been shown to improve cognitive performance on encoding and retrieval tasks. [[Morris water navigation task|Morris water maze]] and radial arm water maze studies of [[rodent]]s found that, when compared to [[Sedentary lifestyle|sedentary]] animals, exercised mice showed improved performance traversing the water maze and displayed enhanced memory for the location of an escape platform.<ref name=\"Berchtold\">Berchtold, N. C., Castello, N., & Cotman, C. W. (2010). [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2857396/ Exercise and time-dependent benefits to learning and memory]. ''Neuroscience'' 167, 588\u2013597.</ref> Likewise, human studies have shown that cognitive performance is improved due to [[Human physiology|physiological]] arousal, which speeded mental processes and enhanced memory storage and retrieval.<ref>Lambourne, K., & Tomporowski, P. (2010). The effect of exercise-induced arousal on cognitive task performance: A meta-regression analysis. Brainresearch, 1341, 1 2 \u2013 2 4.</ref>  Ongoing exercise interventions have been found to favourably impact memory processes in older adults<ref>Colcombe, S. J., Kramer, A. F. (2003). [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Arthur_Kramer2/publication/10833611_Fitness_Effects_on_the_Cognitive_Function_of_Older_Adults_A_Meta-Analytic_Study/links/0fcfd50da2a5b0ae48000000/Fitness-Effects-on-the-Cognitive-Function-of-Older-Adults-A-Meta-Analytic-Study.pdf Fitness effects on the cognitive function of older adults: a meta-analytic study]. ''Psychol. Sci''. 14, 125\u2013130.</ref> and children.<ref>Hillman, C .H., Castelli, D. M., Buck, S. M. (2005). [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Darla_Castelli/publication/7481314_Aerobic_Fitness_and_Neurocognitive_Function_in_Healthy_Preadolescent_Children/links/0fcfd50aa31f620049000000.pdf Aerobic fitness and neurocognitive function in healthy preadolescent children]. ''Med. Sci. Sports Exerc.'' 37, 1967\u20131974.</ref>\n\nExercise has been found to positively regulate [[hippocampus|hippocampal]] [[neurogenesis]],<ref>van Praag H, Kempermann G, Gage FH. 1999b. [http://www.rg-40.com/Running_Increases.htm Running increases cell proliferation and neurogenesis in the adult mouse dentate gyrus]. Nat Neurosci 2:266\u2013270.</ref> which is considered an explanation for the positive influence of physical activities on memory performance. Hippocampus-dependent learning, for example, can promote the survival of newborn neurons which may serve as a foundation for the formation of new memories.<ref>Van der Borght, K., Havekes, R., Bos, T., Eggen, B. J., & Van der Zee, E. A. (2007). [https://www.rug.nl/research/portal/files/3623253/2007BehavNeuroscivdBorght.pdf Exercise Improves Memory Acquisition and Retrieval in the Y-Maze Task: Relationship With Hippocampal Neurogenesis]. ''Behavioral Neuroscience'', 121 (2), 324\u2013334.</ref>  Exercise has been found to increase the level of [[brain-derived neurotrophic factor]] (BDNF) protein in rats, with elevated BDNF levels corresponding with strengthened performance on memory tasks. Data also suggests that BDNF availability at the beginning of [[cognitive test]]ing is related to the overall acquisition of a new cognitive task and may be important in determining the strength of recall in memory tasks.<ref name=\"Berchtold\"/>\n\nHence, brain exercises are found being practiced and adopted early by children to [https://brainy.co.in/sensory-enhancement enhance brain sensory responses] and improve performance of the brain by maintaining its health.\n\nA meta-analysis concluded that specifically [[resistance training]], as compared to cardiovascular exercise, had no measurable effect on working memory.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Landrigan JF, Bell T, Crowe M, Clay OJ, Mirman D |title=Lifting cognition: a meta-analysis of effects of resistance exercise on cognition |journal=Psychol Res |volume= |issue= |pages= |date=2019 |pmid=30627769 |doi=10.1007/s00426-019-01145-x |url=https://www.pure.ed.ac.uk/ws/files/121873388/exercise_accepted_ms_1_.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Mental exercise===\n[[Aristotle]] wrote a [[treatise]] about memory: ''[[On memory|De memoria et reminiscentia]]''.  To improve recollection, he advised that a systematic search should be made and that practice was helpful.  He suggested grouping the items to be remembered in threes and then concentrating upon the central member of each triad (group of three).<ref name=Anne>{{citation |title=Memory |author=Anne Whitehead |chapter=Memory and Inscription |pages=15\u201349}}</ref>\n\nMusic playing has recently gained attention as a possible way to promote brain plasticity. Promising results have been found suggesting that learning music can improve various aspects of memory. For instance, children who participated in one year of instrumental musical training showed improved verbal memory, whereas no such improvement was shown in children who discontinued musical training.<ref>Wan, C. Y., & Schlaug, G. (2010). [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2996135/?c=029 Music making as a tool for promoting brain plasticity across the life span]. The Neuroscientist, 16(5), 566\u2013 577.</ref> Similarly, adults with no previous musical training who participated in individualized piano instruction showed significantly improved performance on tasks designed to test attention and working memory compared to a healthy control group.<ref>Bugos, J. A.,  Perlstein, W. M., McCrae, C. S., Brophy, T. S., & Bedenbaugh, P. H. (2007). [http://upperhandspiano.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Piano-Lessons-Increase-Executive-Function-and-Memory-.pdf Individualized Piano Instruction enhances executive functioning and working memory in older adults]. Aging & Mental Health, 11(4): 464\u2013471.</ref> Evidence suggests that the improvements to verbal, working and long-term memory associated to musical training are a result of the enhanced verbal rehearsal mechanisms musicians possess.<ref>Franklin, M. S., Moore, K., Yip, C., Jonides, J., Rattray, K., & Moher, J. (2008). [http://tanclab.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/7_POM_Franklin_etal2008.pdf The effects of musical training on verbal memory]. Psychology of Music, 36(3), 353 \u2013 365.</ref>\n\nAnother study tested elderly participants in how learning a new activity impacts their memory and mental control.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Park|first=Denise C.|last2=Lodi-Smith|first2=Jennifer|last3=Drew|first3=Linda|last4=Haber|first4=Sara|last5=Hebrank|first5=Andrew|last6=Bischof|first6=G\u00e9rard N.|last7=Aamodt|first7=Whitley|date=January 2014|title=The Impact of Sustained Engagement on Cognitive Function in Older Adults: The Synapse Project|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4154531/|journal=Psychological science|volume=25|issue=1|pages=103\u2013112|doi=10.1177/0956797613499592|issn=0956-7976|pmc=4154531|pmid=24214244}}</ref> They were divided into 5 groups that each spent 15 hours a week doing one of 5 different scenarios: learning digital photography, learning to quilt, learning both digital photography and how to quilt, socializing with others, or doing solitary activities by themselves. It was found that all groups improved with regard to mental control, however learning a new skill(s) lead to improved episodic memory.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cognitive enhancer]]\n*[[Effect of caffeine on memory]]\n*[[Emotion and memory]]\n*[[Music-related memory]]\n*[[Sleep and Memory]]\n*[[Spaced repetition]]\n*[[Working memory training]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Memory}}\n\n[[Category:Memory processes]]\n[[Category:Neuroscience]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toDiet(link changed toDiet (nutrition)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Memory_improvement"}
{"title_page": "2020 United States Senate election in Michigan", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2020 United States Senate election in Michigan\n| country            = Michigan\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = yes\n| previous_election  = 2014 United States Senate election in Michigan\n| previous_year      = 2014\n| next_election      = 2026 United States Senate election in Michigan\n| next_year          = 2026\n| election_date      = November 3, 2020\n| image1             =\n| nominee1           = \n| party1             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      = \n| percentage1        = \n| image2             = \n| nominee2           = \n| party2             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      = \n| percentage2        = \n| map_image          = <!--add map after election-->\n| map_size           =\n| map_caption        = County results\n| title              = U.S. Senator\n| before_election    = [[Gary Peters]]\n| before_party       = Democratic Party (United States)\n| after_election     = \n| after_party        = \n}}\n{{ElectionsMI}}\n\nThe '''2020 United States Senate election in Michigan''' will be held on November 3, 2020, to elect a member of the [[United States Senate]] to represent the State of [[Michigan]], concurrently with the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 U.S. presidential election]], as well as [[2020 United States Senate elections|other elections]] to the United States Senate in other states, [[2020 United States House of Representatives elections|elections]] to the [[United States House of Representatives]], and various [[2020 United States elections#State elections|state]] and [[2020 United States elections#Local elections|local elections]].\n\n[[Gary Peters]], incumbent Democratic Senator, is one of two Democratic Senators facing re-election in 2020 in a state President [[Donald Trump]] carried in 2016 (the other being [[Doug Jones (politician)|Doug Jones]] of Alabama).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/campaigns/trump-won-michigan-2016-matter-gary-peters-2020|title=Trump won Michigan in 2016. Does that matter for Gary Peters in 2020?|first1=Simone|last1=Path\u00e9|first2=Simone|last2=Path\u00e9|date=January 31, 2019|via=www.rollcall.com}}</ref> The primary is scheduled for August 4.<ref>{{cite web |title=United States Senate election in Michigan, 2020 (August 4 Democratic primary) |url=https://ballotpedia.org/United_States_Senate_election_in_Michigan,_2020_(August_4_Democratic_primary) |website=ballotpedia.org |accessdate=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The filing deadline for candidates to run in the August primary is April 21.<ref>https://www.michigan.gov/documents/sos/Filing_Req_For_US_Senator2020_REDO_659727_7.pdf</ref>\n\n==Democratic primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n*[[Gary Peters]], incumbent U.S. Senator<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carlson|first1=Kate|title=Peters, Upton slam Trump\u2019s emergency declaration|url=https://www.hollandsentinel.com/news/20190218/peters-upton-slam-trumps-emergency-declaration|newspaper=Holland Sentinel|date=February 18, 2019|accessdate=April 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|last1=Peters|first1=Gary|title=Incumbent Senator Gary Peters files for re-election|url=https://www.twitter.com/GaryPeters/status/1213163205922578433|date=January 3, 2020|accessdate=January 3, 2019|user=GaryPeters|number=1213163205922578433}}</ref>\n\n====Declined====\n*[[Abdul El-Sayed]], former executive director of the Detroit Department of Health and Wellness Promotion and candidate for [[Governor of Michigan]] in [[2018 Michigan gubernatorial election#Democratic primary|2018]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dovere|first1=Edward-Isaac|authorlink=Edward-Isaac Dovere|title=How the Democrats Took Back Michigan|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/11/how-democrats-won-big-michigan-midterms/576043/|publisher=The Atlantic|date=November 18, 2018|accessdate=November 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Endorsements===\n{{Endorsements box\n|title=Gary Peters\n|list=\n;U.S. federal officials \n* [[Brian Schatz]], U.S. Senator (D-HI)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/brianschatz/status/1136687276442832896?lang=en|title=Gary Peters is an extraordinary Senator for the state of Michigan. He\u2019s great on climate, national security, and has served as an officer in the Navy reserve. Republicans are targeting him. Can you please send him some bucks?https://petersformichigan.com|first=Brian|last=Schatz|date=June 6, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Debbie Stabenow]], U.S. Senator (D-MI)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/stabenow/status/1226687315411685379|title=Service to others. Delivering results and getting things done. I can't think of a better way to describe @GaryPeters and his tireless commitment to Michigan. Let's do everything we can to have Gary's back this November!|first=Debbie|last=Stabenow|date=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n; Organizations\n* [[Clean Water Action]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Brady-Enerson|first=Mary|title=Clean Water Action Endorses Gary Peters for US Senate|url=https://www.cleanwateraction.org/releases/clean-water-action-endorses-gary-peters-us-senate|website=Clean Water Action|date=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Council for a Livable World]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Senate Candidates - Council for a Livable World|url=https://livableworld.org/meet-the-candidates/senate-candidates/|website=Council for a Livable World}}</ref>\n* [[End Citizens United]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Muller |first1=Tiffany |title=End Citizens United Endorses Four U.S. Senators for Reelection |url=https://endcitizensunited.org/press-releases/end-citizens-united-endorses-four-u-s-senators-reelection/ |website=End Citizens United |date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Human Rights Campaign]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Acosta|first1=Lucas|title=HRC Announces Senate Endorsements in Effort to Achieve Pro-Equality Majority|url=https://www.hrc.org/blog/hrc-announces-senate-endorsements-in-effort-to-achieve-pro-equality-majorit|website=Human Rights Campaign|language=en|date=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[League of Conservation Voters]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Burke|first=Holly|url=https://www.lcv.org/article/lcv-action-fund-endorses-senator-gary-peters-re-election/|title=LCV Action Fund Endorses Senator Gary Peters for Re-Election|work=[[League of Conservation Voters]]|date=February 25, 2019|accessdate=March 16, 2019}}</ref>\\\n* [[Michigan Education Association]]<ref>{{cite web|title=MEA announces initial federal candidate recommendations|url=https://mea.org/mea-announces-initial-federal-candidate-recommendations/|website=Michigan Education Association|date=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[National Organization for Women]]<ref>{{cite web|title=2020 Federal Endorsements - NOW PAC|url=https://www.nowpac.org/federal2020|website=nowpac.org}}</ref>\n* [[Planned Parenthood Action Fund]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Axelrod |first1=Tal |title=Planned Parenthood issues first wave of 2020 House, Senate endorsements |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/465134-planned-parenthood-backs-dozens-of-house-senate-candidates-in-first-wave-of |website=TheHill |language=en |date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[NARAL Pro-Choice America]]<ref>{{cite web|title=NARAL Pro-Choice America Endorses Gary Peters for U.S. Senate - NARAL Pro-Choice America|url=https://www.prochoiceamerica.org/2019/06/17/naral-peters-endorsement/|website=NARAL Pro-Choice America|date=June 17, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Population Connection]]<ref>{{cite web|title=2020 Endorsements|url=https://www.populationconnectionaction.org/2020-endorsements/|website=Population Connection}}</ref>\n* Progressive Women's Alliance of West Michigan <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.progressivewomensalliance.org/endorsements|title=PROGRESSIVE WOMEN'S ALLIANCE &#124; Endorsements|website=prowomall}}</ref>\n* [[Sierra Club]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Sierra Club #ClimateVoter Guide: Endorsements |url=https://www.sierraclubindependentaction.org/endorsements|website=Sierra Club |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[VoteVets.org|VoteVets]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Candidates|url=https://www.votevets.org/candidates|website=VoteVets.org|language=en}}</ref>\n* Voter Protection Project<ref>{{cite web |title=Endorsements - Voter Protection Project|url=https://protectvoting.org/endorsements/ |website=Voter Protection Project}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Results===\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Democratic primary results\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Gary Peters]] (incumbent)\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Republican primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n*Bob Carr, historic preservationist, businessman, nominee for [[Michigan's 1st congressional district]] in [[1996 United States House of Representatives elections|1996]], candidate for the U.S. Senate in [[2018 United States Senate election in Michigan|2018]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fec.gov/data/candidate/S4MI00298/|title=Carr, Bob {{!}}FEC-Candidate Overview,|website=FEC |accessdate=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n\n*[[John E. James|John James]], businessman, Iraq War veteran, nominee for the U.S. Senate in [[2018 United States Senate election in Michigan|2018]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eggert|first1=David|title=James announces Senate run against Sen. Peters in Michigan|url=https://www.apnews.com/8d098bbf15544a5c812804026232b92c|agency=Associated Press|date=June 6, 2019|accessdate=June 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Potential====\n*[[Tom Leonard (Michigan politician)|Tom Leonard]], former [[List of Speakers of the Michigan House of Representatives|Speaker of the Michigan House of Representatives]] and nominee for [[Michigan Attorney General]] in [[2018 Michigan Attorney General election|2018]]<ref name=\"LP\">{{cite news|last1=Path\u00e9|first1=Simone|title=Trump won Michigan in 2016. Does that matt