{"title_page": "Jeremy Allen", "text_new": "[[File:Jeremy Allen.jpg|thumb]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Jeremy Allen\n|             country = Australia\n|            fullname = Jeremy Michael Allen\n|          birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1971|06|11|df=yes}}\n|         birth_place = [[Subiaco, Western Australia|Subiaco]], [[Western Australia]], [[Australia]]\n|            nickname = \n|            heightft = 6\n|          heightinch = 3\n|             heightm = \n|             batting = Right-handed\n|             bowling = Left-arm [[Fast bowling|fast-medium]]\n|                role = [[Bowler (cricket)|Bowler]]\n|               club1 = [[Western Australia cricket team|Western Australia]]\n|               year1 = 1994\u20131996\n|             columns = 2\n|             column1 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n|            matches1 = 1\n|               runs1 = 30\n|            bat avg1 = 30.00\n|           100s/50s1 = 0/0\n|          top score1 = 30\n|         deliveries1 = 120\n|            wickets1 = 0\n|           bowl avg1 = n/a\n|            fivefor1 = 0\n|             tenfor1 = 0\n|       best bowling1 = 0/22\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 0/-\n|             column2 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n|            matches2 = 1\n|               runs2 = 12\n|            bat avg2 = n/a\n|           100s/50s2 = 0/0\n|          top score2 = 12*\n|         deliveries2 = 60\n|            wickets2 = 3\n|           bowl avg2 = 20.66\n|            fivefor2 = 0\n|             tenfor2 = n/a\n|       best bowling2 = 3/62\n|  catches/stumpings2 = 0/-\n|                date = 1 February\n|                year = 2013\n|              source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/5/5687/5687.html CricketArchive\n}}\n'''Jeremy Michael Allen''' (born 11 June 1971) is a former Australian [[cricket]]er. From [[Perth]], Allen represented Western Australia at both under-17 and under-19 level, and played [[Western Australian Grade Cricket|grade cricket]] for Subiaco\u2013Floreat.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/5/5687/Miscellaneous_Matches.html Miscellaneous matches played by Jeremy Allen (16)] \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> A regular player for the state second XI from the early 1990s, he did not make his senior debut until the 1994\u201395 season, playing a [[Australian domestic limited-overs cricket tournament|Mercantile Mutual Cup]] match against [[Queensland cricket team|Queensland]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/5/5687/List_A_Matches.html List A matches played by Jeremy Allen (1)] \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> On debut at the [[WACA Ground]], he took 3/62 from his ten overs to help Western Australia win by a single run.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/59/59751.html Western Australia v Queensland], Mercantile Mutual Cup 1994/95 \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> Despite this performance, Allen did not play any further [[List A cricket|limited-overs]] matches for Western Australia, with the state fast-bowling attack including established players [[Sean Cary]], [[Craig Coulson]], and [[Brendan Julian]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/0/Mercantile_Mutual_Cup_1994-95/Western_Australia_Bowling.html Mercantile Mutual Cup 1994/95: bowling for Western Australia] \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> His only other match at state level came during the 1996\u201397 season of the [[Sheffield Shield]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/5/5687/First-Class_Matches.html First-class matches played by Jeremy Allen (1)] \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> In what was to be his only [[first-class cricket|first-class]] match, he failed to take a wicket against [[Tasmania cricket team|Tasmania]], but did score 30 runs batting tenth in Western Australia's second innings.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/63/63040.html Western Australia v Tasmania], Sheffield Shield 1996/1997 \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> Although he attended the [[Australian Cricket Academy]] in 1996, Allen spent the rest of his career in minor competitions.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/australia/content/player/3956.html Jeremy Allen player profile] \u2013 ESPNcricinfo. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Western Australia first-class cricketers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allen, Jeremy}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Australian cricketers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Perth, Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Western Australia cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sportsmen from Western Australia]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:/Users/siennaallen/Desktop/IMG 1690.jpeg|thumb]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Jeremy Allen\n|             country = Australia\n|            fullname = Jeremy Michael Allen\n|          birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1971|06|11|df=yes}}\n|         birth_place = [[Subiaco, Western Australia|Subiaco]], [[Western Australia]], [[Australia]]\n|            nickname = \n|            heightft = 6\n|          heightinch = 3\n|             heightm = \n|             batting = Right-handed\n|             bowling = Left-arm [[Fast bowling|fast-medium]]\n|                role = [[Bowler (cricket)|Bowler]]\n|               club1 = [[Western Australia cricket team|Western Australia]]\n|               year1 = 1994\u20131996\n|             columns = 2\n|             column1 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n|            matches1 = 1\n|               runs1 = 30\n|            bat avg1 = 30.00\n|           100s/50s1 = 0/0\n|          top score1 = 30\n|         deliveries1 = 120\n|            wickets1 = 0\n|           bowl avg1 = n/a\n|            fivefor1 = 0\n|             tenfor1 = 0\n|       best bowling1 = 0/22\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 0/-\n|             column2 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n|            matches2 = 1\n|               runs2 = 12\n|            bat avg2 = n/a\n|           100s/50s2 = 0/0\n|          top score2 = 12*\n|         deliveries2 = 60\n|            wickets2 = 3\n|           bowl avg2 = 20.66\n|            fivefor2 = 0\n|             tenfor2 = n/a\n|       best bowling2 = 3/62\n|  catches/stumpings2 = 0/-\n|                date = 1 February\n|                year = 2013\n|              source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/5/5687/5687.html CricketArchive\n}}\n'''Jeremy Michael Allen''' (born 11 June 1971) is a former Australian [[cricket]]er. From [[Perth]], Allen represented Western Australia at both under-17 and under-19 level, and played [[Western Australian Grade Cricket|grade cricket]] for Subiaco\u2013Floreat.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/5/5687/Miscellaneous_Matches.html Miscellaneous matches played by Jeremy Allen (16)] \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> A regular player for the state second XI from the early 1990s, he did not make his senior debut until the 1994\u201395 season, playing a [[Australian domestic limited-overs cricket tournament|Mercantile Mutual Cup]] match against [[Queensland cricket team|Queensland]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/5/5687/List_A_Matches.html List A matches played by Jeremy Allen (1)] \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> On debut at the [[WACA Ground]], he took 3/62 from his ten overs to help Western Australia win by a single run.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/59/59751.html Western Australia v Queensland], Mercantile Mutual Cup 1994/95 \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> Despite this performance, Allen did not play any further [[List A cricket|limited-overs]] matches for Western Australia, with the state fast-bowling attack including established players [[Sean Cary]], [[Craig Coulson]], and [[Brendan Julian]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/0/Mercantile_Mutual_Cup_1994-95/Western_Australia_Bowling.html Mercantile Mutual Cup 1994/95: bowling for Western Australia] \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> His only other match at state level came during the 1996\u201397 season of the [[Sheffield Shield]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/5/5687/First-Class_Matches.html First-class matches played by Jeremy Allen (1)] \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> In what was to be his only [[first-class cricket|first-class]] match, he failed to take a wicket against [[Tasmania cricket team|Tasmania]], but did score 30 runs batting tenth in Western Australia's second innings.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/63/63040.html Western Australia v Tasmania], Sheffield Shield 1996/1997 \u2013 CricketArchive. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> Although he attended the [[Australian Cricket Academy]] in 1996, Allen spent the rest of his career in minor competitions.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/australia/content/player/3956.html Jeremy Allen player profile] \u2013 ESPNcricinfo. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Western Australia first-class cricketers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allen, Jeremy}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Australian cricketers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Perth, Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Western Australia cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sportsmen from Western Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Siennaa.911", "label": "safe", "comment": "added a picture", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeremy_Allen"}
{"title_page": "India\u2013United States relations", "text_new": "{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the Republic of India and the United States of America}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox bilateral relations\n|Indo\u2013American|India|USA\n|map=India United States Locator.svg\n|envoytitle1 =[[Indian Ambassador to the United States|Indian Ambassador]]\n|envoy1 = [[Taranjit Singh Sandhu]]<ref>{{cite news |title=New Indian envoy Taranjit Singh Sandhu|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/taranjit-singh-sandhu-appointed-india-s-ambassador-to-the-united-states-11580211462808.html|work=Live Mint |date=29 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n|envoytitle2 = [[United States Ambassador to India|U.S. Ambassador]]\n|envoy2 = [[Kenneth Juster]]\n|mission1=[[Embassy of India, Washington, D.C.|Indian Embassy, Washington, D.C.]]\n|mission2=[[Embassy of the United States, New Delhi|United States Embassy, New Delhi]]\n}}\n[[File:-G7Biarritz (48632275313).jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] with US President [[Donald Trump]] at the [[45th G7 summit|45th G7 in Biarritz]], August 2019.]]\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Delivers Closing Remarks at the India 2+2 Dialogue (43603751185) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Left to right: US Secretary of Defense [[Jim Mattis]], US Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]], Indian Minister of External Affairs [[Sushma Swaraj]], and Indian Defense Minister [[Nirmala Sitharaman]] \n during first ever 2+2 conference at [[New Delhi]] in the year 2018]]\n[[File:Icicles on the Embassy of India.JPG|thumb|upright=1.0|[[Embassy of India in Washington, D.C.|Embassy of India]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]]]\n[[File:US Embassy New Delhi.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|[[Embassy of the United States, New Delhi|U.S. Embassy]] in [[New Delhi]]]]\n\n'''India\u2013United States relations''', also known as '''Indian\u2013American relations''' or '''Indo\u2013American relations''', refers to the [[international relations]] between [[India]] and the [[United States]].\n\nProminent leaders of India's freedom movement had friendly relations with the United States which continued well after independence from the United Kingdom in 1947. In 1954, the United States made [[Pakistan]] a Central Treaty Organization ([[CENTO]]) treaty-ally. India cultivated strategic and military relations with the [[India-Soviet Union relations|Soviet Union]] to counter [[Pakistan\u2013United States relations]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cohen|first1=Stephen P.|title=Superpower Rivalry and Conflict \u2013 Pakistan and the Cold War|publisher=Brookings|isbn=978-0-415-55025-3|pages=76, 77, 78|url=http://www.brookings.edu/~/media/Files/rc/articles/2009/12_pakistan_cold_war_cohen/12_pakistan_cold_war_cohen.pdf}}</ref> In 1961, India became a founding member of the [[Non-Aligned Movement]] to avoid involvement in the [[Cold War]] power-play between the United States and the Soviet Union. The [[Nixon administration]]'s support for Pakistan during the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]] affected relations until the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] in 1991. In the 1990s, Indian [[Foreign relations of India|foreign policy]] adapted to the [[unipolar world]] and developed closer ties with the United States.\n\nIn the twenty-first century, Indian foreign policy has sought to leverage India's strategic autonomy in order to safeguard sovereign rights and promote national interests within a multi-polar world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indianembassy.org/archives_details.php?nid=1743|title=Welcome to Embassy of India, Washington D C, USA|publisher=|accessdate=2 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160326092058/https://www.indianembassy.org/archives_details.php?nid=1743|archive-date=March 26, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dpcc.co.in/pdf/civilnuclearcooperation.pdf|title=The tenets of India's independent foreign policy|website=dpcc.co.in|accessdate=March 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504113146/http://dpcc.co.in/pdf/civilnuclearcooperation.pdf|archive-date=May 4, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Retaining India's Strategic Autonomy|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/columns/Retaining-Indias-Strategic-Autonomy/2015/09/09/article3017314.ece|work=Indian Express|date=8 September 2015}}</ref> Under the administrations of Presidents [[George W. Bush]] and [[Barack Obama]], the United States has demonstrated accommodation to India's core national interests and acknowledged outstanding concerns.<ref>{{cite news|title=One year of Modi Government: Us versus them|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/one-year-of-narendra-modi-government-us-versus-them/|work=Indian Express|date=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIncrease in bilateral [[trade]] & [[investment]], co-operation on [[global security]] matters, inclusion of India in decision-making on matters of global governance ([[United Nations Security Council]]), upgraded representation in trade & investment forums ([[World Bank]], [[International Monetary Fund|IMF]], [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation|APEC]]), admission into multilateral export control regimes ([[MTCR]], [[Wassenaar Arrangement]], [[Australia Group]]) and support for admission in the [[Nuclear Suppliers Group]] and joint-manufacturing through technology sharing arrangements have become key milestones and a measure of speed and advancement on the path to closer US\u2013India relations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Indo-US joint statement after Obama-Modi talks|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/resources/indous-joint-statement-after-us-president-barack-obama-and-prime-minister-narendra-modi-talks/article6821279.ece|work=The Hindu|date=25 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=An India-US Tussle Over Technology Transfer|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/06/an-india-us-tussle-over-technology-transfer/|work=The Diplomat|date=11 June 2015}}</ref> In 2016, India and United States signed the Logistics Exchange Memorandum of Agreement<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2016/08/india-us-sign-logistics-exchange-agreement-what-you-need-to-know/|title=India, US Sign Logistics Exchange Agreement|work=[[The Diplomat]]|accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2016/08/30/asia-pacific/key-step-toward-stronger-defense-ties-u-s-india-ink-military-logistics-agreement/|title=In key step toward stronger defense ties, U.S., India ink military logistics agreement|work=[[The Japan Times]]|accessdate=30 August 2016|date=August 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-india-usa-military-idUSKCN114241|title=U.S., India sign military logistics agreement|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=30 August 2016|date=August 30, 2016}}</ref> and India was declared a Major Defense Partner of the United States.<ref name=\"India US Defence\">{{cite web|title=India, US finalise Major Defence Partner agreement|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-us-major-defence-partner-agreement-manohar-parrikar-ashton-carter-4418019/|work=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=9 December 2016|date=December 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]]'s annual World Affairs survey, India is perceived by [[Americans]] as their sixth favorite nation in the world, with 71% of Americans viewing India favorably in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gallup.com/poll/181961/canada-great-britain-americans-favored-nations.aspx |title=Canada, Great Britain Are Americans' Most Favored Nations |publisher=Gallup.com |date=2015-03-13}}</ref> Gallup polls found that 74% of Americans viewed India favorably in 2017<ref>{{cite web|title=North Korea Remains Least-Popular Country Among Americans|url=http://news.gallup.com/poll/204074/north-korea-remains-least-popular-country-among-americans.aspx|publisher=Gallup.com|accessdate=6 February 2018|language=en-us|date=February 20, 2017}}</ref> and 72% in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Americans' Favorable Views of China Take 12-Point Hit |url=https://news.gallup.com/poll/247559/americans-favorable-views-china-point-hit.aspx |website=Gallup.com |accessdate=8 September 2019 |language=en-us|date=March 11, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn the year 2017, bilateral trade (in both goods & services) grew by 9.8% to reach US$126,100,000,000. India's exports to the US stood at US$76,700,000,000 while USA's exports to India stood at US$49,400,000,000 <ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/us-exports-to-india-increase-19-trump-admin-still-cries-foul-over-tariffs-118040500070_1.html | title=US exports to India increase 19%, Trump admin still cries foul over tariffs| newspaper=Business Standard India| date=April 5, 2018| last1=India| first1=Press Trust of}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://ustr.gov/countries-regions/south-central-asia/india# | title=India &#124; United States Trade Representative}}</ref>\n\n{{toc limit|3}}\n\n== History ==\n\n=== British Raj ===\n[[File:Swami Vivekananda at Parliament of Religions.jpg|thumb|[[Swami Vivekananda]] at the Parliament of Religions with [[Virchand Gandhi]] and Hewivitarne Dharmapala]]\nThe relationships between India in the colonial days of the [[British Rule over India]] and the United States were thin.<ref>Holden Furber, \"Historical and Cultural Aspects of Indo-American Relations,\" ''Journal of the University of Bombay'' (1965), Vol. 34 Issue 67/68, pp 95-116.</ref> [[Swami Vivekananda]] promoted [[Yoga]] and [[Vedanta]] in the United States at the [[Parliament of the World's Religions|World's Parliament of Religions]] in [[Chicago]], during the [[World Columbian Exposition|World's Fair]] in 1893. [[Mark Twain]] visited India in 1896<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.twainquotes.com/SpeechIndex.html |title=Chronology of Known Mark Twain Speeches, Public Readings, and Lectures |author=Barbara Schmidt |publisher=marktwainquotes.com |accessdate=January 1, 2013}}</ref> and described it in his travelogue ''[[Following the Equator]]'' with both revulsion and attraction before concluding that India was the only foreign land he dreamed about or longed to see again.<ref name=\"Global Perspectives\">{{cite book |last1=Gupta |first1=Vipin |last2=Saran |first2=Pankaj |title=Global Perspectives on the United States: A Nation by Nation Survey, Volume 1 |year=2007 |publisher=Berkshire Publishing Group |location=Great Barrington, MA |isbn=978-1-933782-06-5 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/globalperspectiv0000unse_j6p5/page/294 294\u2013300] |editors=David Leninson, Karen Christensen |url=https://archive.org/details/globalperspectiv0000unse_j6p5/page/294 }}</ref> Regarding India, Americans learned more from English writer [[Rudyard Kipling]].<ref>Isaacs,  ''Scratches on Our Minds: American Views of China and India'' (1980) p 241</ref> [[Mahatma Gandhi]] had an important influence on the philosophy of non-violence promoted by [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] in the 1950s.\n\nIn the 1930s and early-1940s, the United States gave very strong support to the [[Indian independence movement]] in defiance of the British Empire.<ref>Foster Rhea Dulles, and Gerald E. Ridinger. \"The Anti-Colonial Policies of Franklin D. Roosevelt.\" ''Political Science Quarterly'' (1955): 1\u201318. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2145412 in JSTOR]</ref><ref>Kenton J. Clymer, ''Quest for Freedom: The United States and India's Independence'' (2013).</ref> The first significant immigration from India [[Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965|before 1965]] involved Sikh farmers going to [[California]] in the early-twentieth century.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gonzales |first1=Juan L. |last2=Jr |year=1986 |title=Asian Indian Immigration Patterns: The Origins of the Sikh Community in California |journal=International Migration Review |volume=20 |issue=1|pages=40\u201354 |jstor=2545683|doi=10.1177/019791838602000103 }}</ref>\n\n==== World War II ====\n[[File:Shops in Calcutta in 1945.jpg|thumb|American GIs at a market in Calcutta (now [[Kolkata]]) in 1945.]]\nEverything changed during [[World War II]], when India became the main base for the American [[China Burma India Theater]] (CBI) in the war against [[Japan]]. Tens of thousands of American servicemen arrived, bringing all sorts of advanced technology, and money; they left in 1945. Serious tension erupted over American demands, led by [[President of the United States|US President]] [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], that India be given independence, a proposition [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]] [[Winston Churchill]] vehemently rejected. For years, Roosevelt had encouraged British disengagement from India. The American position was based on principled opposition to colonialism, practical concern for the outcome of the war, and the expectation of a large American role in a post-colonial era. However, in 1942 when the [[Indian National Congress]] launched a [[Quit India]] movement, the British authorities immediately arrested tens of thousands of activists. Meanwhile, India became the main American staging base for aid to [[China]]. Churchill threatened to resign if Roosevelt pushed too hard, so Roosevelt backed down.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rubin |first1=Eric S. |year=2011 |title=America, Britain, and Swaraj: Anglo-American Relations and Indian Independence, 1939\u20131945 |url = |journal=India Review |volume=10 |issue=1|pages=40\u201380 |doi=10.1080/14736489.2011.548245}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Arthur Herman |title=Gandhi & Churchill: The Epic Rivalry That Destroyed an Empire and Forged Our Age |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hdPmzLtU5G4C |year=2008 |publisher=Random House Digital, Inc. |pages=472\u2013539 |isbn=978-0-553-80463-8}}</ref>\n\n=== Independence (1947\u20131997) ===\n{{Further|History of Indian foreign relations}}\n[[File:Photograph of President Truman and Indian Prime Minister Jawaharlal Nehru, with Nehru's sister, Madame Pandit, waving... - NARA - 200154.tif|thumb|US President [[Harry S. Truman]] and Indian Prime Minister [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] in Washington, 1949, with Nehru's sister, [[Vijayalakshmi Pandit]]  Indian ambassador to the United States.]]\nThe United States under the [[Truman administration]] leaned towards favouring India in the late-1940s as a consequence of most U.S. planners seeing India more valuable diplomatically than neighboring Pakistan.<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert J. McMahon|title=The Cold War on the Periphery: The United States, India, and Pakistan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Deq32J9P4ZMC|date=1 June 2010|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-51467-5|page=11|quote=Despite keen attention to Pakistan's potential strategic significance, most US planners rated India as far the more valuable diplomatic prize. American policy towards the subcontinent consequently leaned in favour of India throughout the late-1940s. The opening of bilateral relations with New Delhi and [[Karachi]] and the reasons for the initial Truman administration tilt toward the former will be explored in the next chapter.}}</ref> However, during the [[Cold War]] Nehru's policy of neutrality was awkward to many American observers. American officials perceived India's policy of non-alignment negatively. Ambassador Henry F. Grady told then-Indian Prime Minister [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] that the United States did not consider neutrality to be an acceptable position. Grady told the State Department in December 1947 that he had informed Nehru \"that this is a question that cannot be straddled and that India should get on the democratic side immediately\".<ref name=\"Robert McMahon\">{{cite book|last1=McMahon|first1=Robert J.|title=The Cold War on the Periphery: The United States, India, and Pakistan|date=13 August 2013|publisher=Columbia University Press|page=40|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Deq32J9P4ZMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=28 November 2015|isbn=9780231514675}}</ref>  In 1948, Nehru rejected American suggestions for resolving the Kashmir crisis via third party mediation.\n\nNehru's 1949 tour of the United States was \"an undiplomatic disaster\" that left bad feelings on both sides.<ref>H.W. Brands, ''Inside the Cold War'' (1991) p 202\u201305, quote p 204</ref> Nehru and his top aide [[V. K. Krishna Menon]] discussed whether India should \"align with United States 'somewhat' and build up our economic and military strength.\"<ref>Sarvepalli Gopal, ''Jawaharlal Nehru: A Biography. 1947-1956. Volume Two'' (1979) 2: 59.</ref>  The [[Presidency of Harry S. Truman|Truman administration]] was quite favorable and indicated it would give Nehru anything he asked for. He proudly refused, and thereby forfeited the chance for a gift of one million tons of wheat. The American Secretary of State [[Dean Acheson]] recognized Nehru's potential world role but added that he was \"one of the most difficult men with whom I have ever had to deal.\"<ref>Gopal, ''Nehru'' 2:60.</ref> The American visit had some benefits in that Nehru gained widespread understanding and support for his nation, and he himself gained a much deeper understanding of the American outlook.<ref>Rudra Chaudhuri, ''Forged in crisis: India and the United States since 1947'' (2014) pp 25-47.</ref>\n\nIndia rejected the American advice that it should not recognise the Communist conquest of China, but it did back the US when it supported the 1950 United Nations resolution condemning [[North Korea]]'s aggression in the [[Korean War]]. India tried to act as a broker to help end that war, and served as a conduit for diplomatic messages between the US and China. Although no Indian troops took part in the war, India did send a Medical Corps of 346 army doctors to help the UN side.<ref>[https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/open-page/the-doctor-heroes-of-war/article17529390.ece The Hindu, 19 March 2017 - The Doctor Heroes of War]</ref> Meanwhile, poor harvests forced India to ask for American aid for its food security, which was given [[Food for Peace#Public Law 480 (1954)|starting in 1950]].<ref>Brands, ''Inside the Cold War'' (1991) pp 212\u201324, 229</ref> In the first dozen years of Indian independence (1947\u201359), the US provided $1,700,000,000 in aid; including $931,000,000 in food. The Soviet Union provided about half as much in monetary terms, however made much larger contributions in kind, taking the form of infrastructural aid, soft loans, technical knowledge transfer, economic planning and skills involved in the areas of [[Bokaro Steel Plant|steel]] [[Steel mill|mills]], [[HMT (company)|machine building]], hydroelectric power and other heavy industries- especially [[Bhabha Atomic Research Centre|nuclear energy]] and [[ISRO|space research]].<ref>Richard P. Stebbins, ''The United States in World Affairs: 1959'' (1960) p 297</ref> In 1961, the US pledged $1,000,000,000 in development loans, in addition to $1,300,000,000 of free food.<ref>Richard P. Stebbins, ''The United States in World Affairs: 1961'' (1962) p 208</ref>\n[[File:Indo US.jpg|thumb|left|Prime Minister Jawaharlal Nehru receiving President Dwight D. Eisenhower at Parliament House, before the President's address to a joint session of Parliament, 1959.]]\nIn 1959, [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] became the first US President to visit India to strengthen the staggering ties between the two nations. He was so supportive that the ''[[New York Times]]'' remarked, \"It did not seem to matter much whether Nehru had actually requested or been given a guarantee that the US would help India to meet further Chinese Communist aggression. What mattered was the obvious strengthening of Indian\u2013American friendship to a point where no such guarantee was necessary.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-01-21/us/28006522_1_strategic-counter-nuclear-fuel-supply-visit |title=Strategic Counter Nuclear Fuel Supply Visit |work=The Times of India |date=21 January 2009 |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref>\n[[File:JKGalbraith JFK.jpg|right|thumb|[[John Kenneth Galbraith]] ''(far left)'', as US ambassador to India, with President John F. Kennedy, Vice-President Lyndon B. Johnson and Prime Minister Jawaharlal Nehru of India, 1961]]\nDuring [[John F. Kennedy]]'s Presidency (1961\u201363), India was considered a strategic partner and counterweight to the rise of Communist China. Kennedy said,\n\n{{quote|Chinese Communists have been moving ahead the last 10 years. India has been making some progress, but if India does not succeed with her 450 million people, if she can't make freedom work, then people around the world are going to determine, particularly in the underdeveloped world, that the only way they can develop their resources is through the Communist system.}}\n\nThe [[Timeline of the presidency of John F. Kennedy|Kennedy administration]] openly supported India during the [[Sino-Indian War|1962 Sino-Indian war]] and considered the Chinese action as \"blatant Chinese Communist aggression against India\".<ref name=ht16a13>{{cite news|title=India used US spy planes to map Chinese incursion in Sino-Indian war|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/Americas/India-used-US-spy-planes-to-map-Chinese-incursion-in-1962-war/Article1-1108481.aspx|accessdate=16 August 2013|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=16 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nehru permitted CIA spy planes to use Indian air base|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/nehru-permitted-cia-spy-planes-to-use-indian-air-base-113081600225_1.html|accessdate=16 August 2013|newspaper=Business Standard|date=16 August 2013}}</ref> The [[United States Air Force]] flew in arms, ammunition and clothing supplies to the Indian troops and the [[United States Navy]] even sent the [[USS Kitty Hawk (CV-63)|USS ''Kitty Hawk'']] [[aircraft carrier]] from the [[Pacific Ocean]] to protect India, only to recall it back before it reached the [[Bay of Bengal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/special/the-untold-story-how-the-us-came-to-indias-aid-in-1962/20121204.htm |title=The Untold Story- How the US came to India's aid |publisher=Rediff.com |date=4 December 2012 |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Sukumaran |first=R. |url=http://www.idsa.in/system/files/strategicanalysis_sukumaran_0903.pdf |title=The 1962 India-China War and Kargil 1999: Restrictions on the Use of Air Power |date=July\u2013September 2003 |volume=27 |journal=Strategic Analysis |accessdate=2013-12-17 |issue=3|pages=332\u2013356 |doi=10.1080/09700160308450094 }}</ref> In a May 1963 [[National Security Council (USA)|National Security Council]] meeting, the United States discussed contingency planning that could be implemented in the event of another Chinese attack on India. [[Secretary of Defense|Defense Secretary]] [[Robert McNamara]] and General [[Maxwell Taylor]] advised the president to use [[nuclear weapons]] should the Americans intervene in such a situation. Kennedy insisted that Washington defend India as it would any ally, saying, \"We ''should'' defend India, and therefore we ''will'' defend India.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2005/08/27/2003269368|title=JFK, aides considered nuclear arms in China-India clash|publisher=|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iacfpa.org/p_news/nit/iacpa-archieve/2005/09/02/diplo3-02092005.shtml|title=Welcome to IACFPA.ORG|publisher=|accessdate=27 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604032213/http://www.iacfpa.org/p_news/nit/iacpa-archieve/2005/09/02/diplo3-02092005.shtml|archive-date=June 4, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Kennedy's ambassador to India was the noted liberal economist [[John Kenneth Galbraith]], who was considered close to India.<ref>{{cite web|first=Tanvi |last=Madan |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/personality-in-its-place/1116958/ |title=Personality in its place |publisher=The Indian Express |date=2013-05-17 |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref> While in India, Galbraith helped establish one of the first Indian computer science departments, at the [[IIT Kanpur|Indian Institute of Technology in Kanpur, Uttar Pradesh]]. As an economist, he also presided over the (at the time) largest US foreign aid program to any country.\n[[File:Arrival ceremony for Prime Minister Indira Gandhi - NARA - 194389.tif|thumb|left|upright=0.7|US President [[Richard Nixon]] at the arrival ceremony for Indian Prime Minister [[Indira Gandhi]], on the South Lawn of the White House, 1971.]]\nFollowing the [[assassination of John F. Kennedy|assassination of Kennedy in 1963]], Indo-US relations deteriorated gradually. While Kennedy's successor [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] sought to maintain relations with India to counter Communist China,<ref name=upppav>{{cite web|url=http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl1810/18100490.htm |title=Lyndon Johnson and India |publisher=Frontline.in |date= |accessdate=2015-12-30}}</ref> he also sought to strengthen ties with Pakistan with the hopes of easing tensions with China and weakening India's growing military buildup as well.<ref name=upppav /> Relations then hit an all-time low under the [[Nixon administration]] in the early 1970s. [[Richard Nixon]] shifted away from the neutral stance which his predecessors had taken towards Indo-Pakistani hostilities. He established a very close relationship with Pakistan, aiding it militarily and economically, as India, now under the leadership of [[Indira Gandhi]], was seen as leaning towards the Soviet Union. He considered Pakistan as a very important ally to counter Soviet influence in the Indian subcontinent and establish ties with China, with whom Pakistan was very close.<ref>{{cite web|title=Foreign Relations, 1969\u20131976, Volume E-7, Documents on South Asia, 1969\u20131972|url=https://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ho/frus/nixon/e7/48213.htm|publisher=[[US State Department]]|accessdate=20 October 2009}}</ref> The frosty personal relationship between Nixon and Indira further contributed to the poor relationship between the two nations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4633263.stm |title=Nixon's dislike of 'witch' Indira |publisher=BBC News |date=2005-06-29 |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref> During the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971|1971 Indo-Pakistani War]], the US openly supported Pakistan and even deployed its aircraft carrier [[USS Enterprise (CVN-65)|USS ''Enterprise'']] towards the Bay of Bengal, which was seen as a show of force by the US in support of the beleaguered [[West Pakistan]]i forces. Later in 1974, India conducted its first nuclear test, [[Smiling Buddha]], which was opposed by the US, however it also concluded that the test did not violate any agreement and proceeded with a June 1974 shipment of [[enriched uranium]] for the [[Tarapur Atomic Power Station|Tarapur]] reactor.<ref name=prolifimpact>{{cite book|last=Perkovich|first=George|title=India's nuclear bomb: the impact on global proliferation|year=2002|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-23210-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ripples in the nuclear pond|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=x6ZSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LX8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=7191%2C5606996 |accessdate=5 September 2011 |newspaper=The Deseret News|date=22 May 1974}}</ref>\n[[File:Jimmy Carter with Prime Minister of India, Morarji Desai - NARA - 179821.tif|right|thumb|Indian Prime Minister [[Morarji Desai]] with US President [[Jimmy Carter]], at the [[Oval office]], 1978.]]\nIn the late 1970s, with the [[Janata Party]] leader [[Morarji Desai]] becoming the Prime Minister, India improved its relations with the US, now led by [[Jimmy Carter]], despite the latter signing an order in 1978 barring nuclear material from being exported to India due to India's non-proliferation record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=30713 |title=Executive Order 12055 \u2013 Export of Special Nuclear Material to India |work=The American Presidency Project |publisher=Ucsb.edu |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref>\n\nDespite the return of Indira Gandhi to power in 1980, the relations between the two countries continued to improve gradually, although India did not support the United States in its role in the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War|Soviet invasion and occupation of Afghanistan]]. The [[Reagan Administration]] led by US President [[Ronald Reagan]] provided limited assistance to India. India sounded out Washington on the purchase of a range of US defence technology, including F-5 aircraft, super computers, night vision goggles and radars. In 1984 Washington approved the supply of selected technology to India including gas turbines for naval frigates and engines for prototypes for India's light combat aircraft. There were also unpublicised transfers of technology, including the engagement of a US company, Continental Electronics, to design and build a new VLF communications station at Tirunelveli in Tamil Nadu, which was commissioned in the late 1980s.<ref>{{cite book|author=David Brewster|url=https://www.academia.edu/7698761 |title=India's Ocean: the Story of India's Bid for Regional Leadership. Retrieved 30 August 2014}}</ref> However, it was not until the late 1990s that there was a significant effort by both countries to improve relations with each other.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globaledge.msu.edu/Countries/India/government |title=India: Government |work=globalEDGE |publisher=Michigan State University |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref>\n\n=== NDA I and II governments (1998\u20132004) ===\nSoon after [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]] became Indian Prime Minister, he authorised [[Pokhran-II|nuclear weapons testing]] at [[Pokhran]]. The United States strongly condemned this testing, promised sanctions, and voted in favour of a [[United Nations Security Council]] Resolution condemning the tests. President [[Bill Clinton]] imposed [[economic sanctions]] on India, including cutting off all military and economic aid, freezing loans by American banks to state-owned Indian companies, prohibiting loans to the Indian government for all except food purchases, prohibiting American aerospace technology and uranium exports to India, and requiring the US to oppose all loan requests by India to international lending agencies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/clinton-imposes-full-sanctionsindia/22222/ |title=Clinton Imposes Full Sanctions On India |work=Business Standard |date=1998-05-14 |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref> However, these sanctions proved ineffective \u2013 India was experiencing a strong economic rise, and its trade with the US only constituted a small portion of its [[gross domestic product|GDP]]. Only [[Japan]] joined the US in imposing direct sanctions, while most other nations continued to trade with India. The sanctions were soon lifted. Afterward, the Clinton administration and Prime Minister Vajpayee exchanged representatives to help rebuild relations.\n\n[[File:Bush Vajpayee Oval Office.jpg|thumb|Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee with US President George W. Bush in the [[Oval office]], 2001.]]\nIndia emerged in the 21st century as increasingly vital to core US foreign policy interests. India, a dominant actor in its region, and the home of more than one billion citizens, is now often characterised as a nascent Great Power and an \"indispensable partner\" of the US, one that many analysts view as a potential counterweight to the growing clout of [[China]].\n\nIn March 2000, U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]] visited India, undertaking bilateral and economic discussions with Prime Minister Vajpayee. During the visit, the [[Indo-US Science & Technology Forum]] was established.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Neureiter|first=Norman|author2=Michael Cheetham|title=The Indo-U.S. Science and Technology Forum as a Model for Bilateral Cooperation|journal=Science & Diplomacy|date=2013-12-16|volume=2|issue=4|url=http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/editorial/2013/indo-us-science-and-technology-forum-model-for-bilateral-cooperation}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of improved diplomatic relations with the Bush Administration, India agreed to allow close international monitoring of its nuclear weapons development, although it has refused to give up its current nuclear arsenal.<ref>{{cite web|last=Limaye |first=Satu P. |url=http://csis.org/files/media/csis/pubs/0104qus_india.pdf |title=U.S.-India Relations: Visible to the Naked Eye |publisher=Asia-Pacific Center for Security Studies |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref> In 2004, the US decided to grant [[Major non-NATO ally]] (MNNA) status to Pakistan. The US extended the MNNA strategic working relationship to India but the offer was turned down.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us/US-mulls-India-as-non-Nato-ally/articleshow/576446.cms|title=US mulls India as non-Nato ally|work=The Times of India|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/In-US-India-strategic-tango-its-passion-vs-caution/articleshow/14101814.cms|title=In US-India strategic tango, it's passion vs caution|work=The Times of India|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[September 11 attacks]] against the US in 2001, President [[George W. Bush]] collaborated closely with India in controlling and policing the strategically critical [[Indian Ocean]] sea lanes from the [[Suez Canal]] to [[Singapore]].\n\n=== UPA I & II governments (2004\u20132014) ===\nDuring the tenure of the [[George W. Bush administration]], relations between India and the United States were seen to have blossomed, primarily over common concerns regarding growing [[Islamic extremism]], energy security, and climate change.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ejaz |first=Ahmad |url=http://pu.edu.pk/images/journal/studies/PDF-FILES/4%20-%20Ahmad%20Ejaz%20Artical-2_v13No1.pdf |title=United States-India Relations: An expanding strategic partnership |journal=Pakistan Vision |volume=13 |accessdate=2013-12-17 |issue=1}}</ref> [[George W. Bush]] commented, \"India is a great example of democracy. It is very devout, has diverse religious heads, but everyone is comfortable about their religion. The world needs India\".<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/money/2006/mar/03bush2.htm The world needs India: Bush] 3 March 2006</ref> [[Fareed Zakaria]], in his book ''[[The Post-American World]]'', described George W. Bush as \"being the most pro-Indian president in American history.\"<ref>Zakaria, Fareed, The Post-American World, 2008 Cahapter VII, pp. 225-226</ref> Similar sentiments are echoed by [[Rejaul Karim Laskar]], a scholar of Indian foreign policy and ideologue of [[Indian National Congress|India's Congress Party]] \u2013 the largest constituent of the [[United Progressive Alliance (India)|UPA]]. According to [[Rejaul Karim Laskar|Laskar]], the [[United Progressive Alliance (India)|UPA]] rule has seen a \"transformation in bilateral ties with the US\", as a result of which the relations now covers \"a wide range of issues, including high technology, space, education, agriculture, trade, clean energy, counter-terrorism, etc\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Laskar|first1=Rejaul|title=Promoting National Interest Through Diplomacy|journal=Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary Diplomatist|date=December 2013|volume=1|issue=9|page=60}}</ref>\n\nAfter the December [[2004 tsunami]], the US and Indian navies cooperated in search and rescue operations and in the reconstruction of affected areas.\n\nSince 2004, Washington and New Delhi have been pursuing a \"strategic partnership\" that is based on shared values and generally convergent geopolitical interests. Numerous economic, security, and global initiatives \u2013 including plans for civilian nuclear cooperation \u2013 are underway. This latter initiative, first launched in 2005, reversed three decades of American non-proliferation policy. Also in 2005, the United States and India signed a ten-year defence framework agreement, with the goal of expanding bilateral security cooperation. The two countries engaged in numerous and unprecedented combined military exercises, and major US arms sales to India were concluded. An [[Open Skies Agreement]] was signed in April 2005, enhancing trade, tourism, and business via the increased number of flights, and [[Air India]] purchased 68 US [[Boeing]] aircraft at a cost of $8 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boeing.co.in/Boeing-in-India/About-Boeing-in-India |title=About Boeing in India |publisher=Boeing India |accessdate=2013-12-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209045547/http://www.boeing.co.in/Boeing-in-India/About-Boeing-in-India |archivedate=February 9, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The United States and India also signed a bilateral Agreement on Science and Technology Cooperation in 2005.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dolan|first=Bridget M.|title=Science and Technology Agreements as Tools for Science Diplomacy|journal=Science & Diplomacy|date=10 December 2012|volume=1|issue=4|url=http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/article/2012/science-and-technology-agreements-tools-for-science-diplomacy}}</ref> After [[Hurricane Katrina]], India donated $5 million to the [[American Red Cross]] and sent two planeloads of relief supplies and materials to help.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ia.rediff.com/news/2005/sep/03katrina.htm |title=India pledges 5 million dollars for Katrina relief |publisher=Ia.rediff.com |date=3 September 2005 |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref> Then, on 1 March 2006, President Bush made another diplomatic visit to further expand relations between India and the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipcs.org/pdf_file/news_archive/mar_06_nuclear.pdf|title=March 2006 news archive|author=|date=|website=ipcs.org|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bush meets Pranab Mukherjee.jpg|thumb|left|Indian Minister of External Affairs [[Pranab Mukherjee]] with US President George W. Bush, March 2008]]\nThe value of all bilateral trade tripled from 2004 to 2008 and continues to grow, while significant two-way investment also grows and flourishes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ustr.gov/countries-regions/south-central-asia/india |title=U.S.-India Bilateral Trade and Investment |publisher=Office of the United States Trade Representative |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref>\n\nThe influence of a large Indian-American community is reflected in the largest country-specific caucus in the [[United States Congress]], while between 2009\u20132010 more than 100,000 Indian students have attended American colleges and universities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://trade.gov/press/press-releases/2011/commerce-trade-official-to-lead-education-trade-mission-to-india-100711.asp |title=Commerce Trade Official to Lead Education Trade Mission to India |publisher=International Trade Administration |date=2011-10-06 |accessdate=2013-12-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017060809/http://www.trade.gov/press/press%2Dreleases/2011/commerce-trade-official-to-lead-education-trade-mission-to-india-100711.asp |archive-date=October 17, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2010, President [[Barack Obama]] visited India and addressed a joint session of the Indian Parliament,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amritt.com/india-business-guide/barack-obama-india-trip-2010/|title=Barack Obama India Trip 2010|work=Amritt, Inc.|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref> where he backed [[Reform of the United Nations Security Council|India's bid for a permanent seat]] on the [[United Nations Security Council]].<ref>{{cite news|agency=AP |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/obama-supports-india-on-un-security-council-2128544.html |title=Obama supports India on UN Security Council |work=The Independent |date=2010-11-08 |accessdate=2013-12-17 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2004 and 2014 Western ''think-tanks'', especially in the US and UK, failed to foresee the swing in electoral voting patterns of the growing middle-class and anticipate the scale of political change in India brought about by improvements in basic education and freedom of the press. According to Michael Kugelman, South and Southeast Asia expert at the Woodrow Wilson International Center, the US was unprepared to meet new challenges in India because of its \"inability to keep pace with the transformations.\"<ref name=\"rt.com\">{{cite news|url=http://rt.com/op-edge/172068-us-india-investment-nsa/|title=The curious case of NSA & Indo-US relations |publisher=RT |date=11 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==== Strategic and military determinants ====\n{{See also|Quadrilateral Security Dialogue}}\n\nIn March 2009, the Obama Administration cleared the US$2.1&nbsp;billion sale of eight [[P-8 Poseidon]]s to India.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/topNews/idUSTRE52F6X520090316|title=U.S. OKs record $2.1 billion arms sale to India|date=16 March 2009|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref> This deal, and the $5&nbsp;billion agreement to provide [[Boeing C-17 Globemaster III|Boeing C-17]] [[military transport aircraft]] and [[General Electric F414]] engines announced during Obama's November 2010 visit, makes the US one of the top three military suppliers to India (after Israel and Russia).<ref>{{cite web|last=Cohen|first=Stephen and Sanil Dasgupta|title=Arms Sales for India|url=http://www.brookings.edu/articles/2011/03_india_cohen_dasgupta.aspx|publisher=Brookings Institution|accessdate=18 March 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110309074634/http://www.brookings.edu/articles/2011/03_india_cohen_dasgupta.aspx|archivedate=March 9, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Indians have raised concerns about contract clauses forbidding the offensive deployment of these systems.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20121120/DEFREG03/311200001/Boeing-Could-Win-Another-Indian-Helicopter-Contract?odyssey=mod_sectionstories|title=Boeing Could Win Another Indian Helicopter Contract |date=20 November 2012}}</ref> India is trying to resolve performance-related issues on the Boeing P-8I that have already been delivered to India.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/pentagon-report-indian-navy-s-new-submarine-hunter-is-ineffective-114012500673_1.html|title=Pentagon report: Indian Navy's new submarine hunter is ineffective| date=25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.strategypage.com/htmw/htnavai/articles/20140205.aspx|title=Naval Air: The Boeing P-8 Stumbles |date=5 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nUS [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]] [[Mike Mullen]] has encouraged stronger military ties between India and the United States, and said that \"India has emerged as an increasingly important strategic partner [of the US]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/001200906101311.htm|title=India has emerged as a strategic partner for U.S.: Mullen|author=|date=|website=The Hindu|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref> US Undersecretary of State [[William Joseph Burns]] also said, \"Never has there been a moment when India and America mattered more to each other.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gsn.nti.org/gsn/nw_20100602_6708.php|title=India, U.S. Launch Strategic Talks \u2013 Global Security Newswire \u2013 NTI|work=NTI: Nuclear Threat Initiative|accessdate=27 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105092451/http://gsn.nti.org/gsn/nw_20100602_6708.php|archive-date=November 5, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Deputy Secretary of Defence, Ashton Carter, during his address to the Asia Society in New York on August 1, 2012, said that India\u2013US relationship has a global scope, in terms of the reach and influence of both countries. He also said that both countries are strengthening the relations between their defence and research organisations.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics/nation/us-india-relationship-is-global-in-scope-pentagon/articleshow/15324037.cms|title=US India relationship is global in scope: Pentagon |date=2 August 2012 |work=The Times Of India}}</ref>\n\n=====Revelations about US spying operations against India =====\n{{Main|CIA activities in India}}\nIndia, in July and November 2013, demanded that the US respond to revelations that the Indian UN mission in New York City and the Indian Embassy in Washington had been targeted for spying.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Security-Watch/terrorism-security/2014/0702/India-recoils-at-reported-NSA-spying-on-its-Hindu-nationalist-party|title=India recoils at reported NSA spying on its Hindu nationalist party |work=Christian Science Monitor |date=3 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 July 2014, U.S. diplomats were summoned by the Indian Ministry of External Affairs to discuss allegations that the National Security Agency had spied upon private individuals and political entities within India.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-summons-u-s-diplomats-1404300559|title=India Summons U.S. Diplomats Over Spying Claims |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=2 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/nsa-snooping-on-bjp-not-to-impact-bilateral-ties-us/1/369611.html|title=US hopes NSA snooping on BJP won't impact bilateral ties |work=India Today  |date=2 July 2014}}</ref> A 2010 document leaked by Edward Snowden and published by the ''Washington Post'' revealed that US intelligence agencies had been authorized to spy on the Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] (who was then the [[Chief minister (India)|Chief Minister]] of [[Gujarat]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2014/07/02/india-usa-idINKBN0F70J820140702|title=India seeks assurances from U.S. over spying reports |publisher=Reuters India |date=3 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-07-02/india-demands-u-s-explanation-after-report-modi-party-spied-on.html|title=India Demands U.S. Explanation After Modi Party Spied On |publisher=Bloomberg |date=3 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[WikiLeaks]] revelations that Western intelligence agencies have used foreign aid workers and staff at NGOs as [[non-official cover]] prompted the Government of India to step-up the monitoring of [[satellite phone]]s and movement of personnel working for humanitarian relief organisations and development aid agencies in the vicinity of sensitive locations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Narendra Modi govt cracks down on NGOs, prepares hitlist|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/modi-govt-prepares-ngo-hitlist/article1-1310127.aspx|work=Hindustan Times|date=24 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The foreign threat|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/the-foreign-threat/|work=The Indian Express|date=15 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Foreign policy issues ====\nAccording to some analysts, India\u2013U.S. relations have been strained over the Obama administration's approach to Pakistan and the handling of the [[Taliban insurgency]] in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest%2BNews/Asia/Story/A1Story20081111-99718.html|title=No call from Obama seen as slight to India|publisher=|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianewsnet.net/news.php?id=2540&sec=1|title=- ANN|accessdate=27 September 2014|url-status=usurped|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615161849/http://www.asianewsnet.net/news.php?id=2540&sec=1|archivedate=June 15, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> India's [[National Security Advisor (India)|National Security Adviser]], [[Mayankote Kelath Narayanan|M.K. Narayanan]], criticised the Obama administration for linking the [[Kashmir dispute]] to the instability in Pakistan and Afghanistan, and said that by doing so, President Obama was \"barking up the wrong tree.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2009-02-05/news/28438459_1_wrong-tree-narayanan-pakistan-and-india |work=The Times Of India |title=Narayanan has barked up the wrong tree now |date=5 February 2009}}</ref> ''Foreign Policy'' in February 2009 also criticised Obama's approach to South Asia, saying that \"India can be a part of the solution rather than part of the problem\" in South Asia. It also suggested that India take a more proactive role in rebuilding [[Afghanistan]], irrespective of the attitude of the Obama Administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2009/02/20/india-needs-a-lot-more-love-from-obama/|title=India needs a lot more love from Obama|author=|date=20 February 2009|website=Foreign Policy|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref> In a clear indication of growing rift between the two countries, India decided not to accept a US invitation to attend a conference on Afghanistan at the end of February 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2009-02/21/content_10866084.htm|title=India not to attend conference on Afghanistan with Pakistan, U.S._English_Xinhua|publisher=|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref> ''[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]'' has also reported that, since the [[2008 Mumbai attacks]], the public mood in India has been to pressure Pakistan more aggressively to take actions against the culprits behind the terrorist attack, and that this might reflect on the upcoming [[2009 Indian general election|Indian general elections in May 2009]]. Consequently, the Obama Administration may find itself at odds with India's rigid stance against terrorism.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601091&sid=a2us2qcyo9nw&refer=india|title=404. Page Not Found \u2013 Bloomberg|author=|date=|website=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIndia and US governments have differed on a variety of regional issues ranging from India's cordial [[India\u2013Iran relations|relations with Iran]] and Russia to foreign policy disagreements relating to Sri Lanka, Maldives, Myanmar and Bangladesh.\n\n[[Robert O. Blake, Jr.|Robert Blake]], [[Assistant Secretary of State for South and Central Asian Affairs]], dismissed any concerns over a rift with India regarding American [[AfPak]] policy. Calling India and the United States \"natural allies\",<ref name=blake1>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/p/sca/rls/remarks/125513.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705085818/http://www.state.gov/p/sca/rls/remarks/125513.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 5, 2009|title=We're sorry, that page can't be found.|website=www.state.gov|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref> Blake said that the United States cannot afford to meet the strategic priorities in Pakistan and Afghanistan at \"the expense of India\".<ref name=blake2>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/p/sca/rls/remarks/125503.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090715110929/http://www.state.gov/p/sca/rls/remarks/125503.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 15, 2009|title=We're sorry, that page can't be found.|website=www.state.gov|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIndia criticised the Obama Administration's decision to limit [[H-1B visa|H-1B (temporary) visas]], and India's then External Affairs Minister [[Pranab Mukherjee]] (later, the [[President of India]] until 2017) said that his country would oppose US \"[[protectionism]]\" at various international forums.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/asiapcf/02/20/india.us.protectionism/index.html|title=India says it will oppose U.S. 'protectionism'|publisher=|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref> India's Commerce Minister, [[Kamal Nath]], said that India may move against Obama's outsourcing policies at the [[World Trade Organization]].<ref>[http://www.hindustantimes.com/StoryPage/StoryPage.aspx?sectionName=HomePage&id=8500ec49-8326-4a88-b41d-fdd74fd2aad3&MatchID1=4934&TeamID1=3&TeamID2=1&MatchType1=1&SeriesID1=1248&MatchID2=4925&TeamID3=4&TeamID4=2&MatchType2=1&SeriesID2=1244&PrimaryID=4934&Headline=India+may+contest+Obama%27s+move+against+outsourcing+in+WTO India may contest Obama's move against outsourcing in WTO] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090501202358/http://www.hindustantimes.com/StoryPage/StoryPage.aspx?sectionName=HomePage&id=8500ec49-8326-4a88-b41d-fdd74fd2aad3&MatchID1=4934&TeamID1=3&TeamID2=1&MatchType1=1&SeriesID1=1248&MatchID2=4925&TeamID3=4&TeamID4=2&MatchType2=1&SeriesID2=1244&PrimaryID=4934&Headline=India+may+contest+Obama%27s+move+against+outsourcing+in+WTO |date=1 May 2009 }}</ref> However, the outsourcing advisory head of [[KPMG]] said that India had no reason to worry, since Obama's statements were directed against \"outsourcing being carried out by manufacturing companies\" and not outsourcing of [[Information technology|IT]]-related services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/obama-on-outsourcing-is-no-reason-to-panic/428626/|title=Obama on outsourcing is no reason to panic|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Obama reiterated his anti-outsourcing views and criticised the current US tax policy \"that says you should pay lower taxes if you create a job in Bangalore, India, than if you create one in Buffalo, New York.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldpoliticsreview.com/article.aspx?id=3924|title=U.S.-India Relations Strained under Obama|publisher=|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref> However, during the [[US India Business Council]] meeting in June 2009, [[U.S. Secretary of State]] Hillary Clinton advocated for stronger economic ties between India and the United States. She also rebuked protectionist policies, saying that \"[United States] will not use the global financial crisis as an excuse to fall back on protectionism. We hope India will work with us to create a more open, equitable set of opportunities for trade between our nations.\"<ref name=Clinton>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090622012521/http://www.state.gov/secretary/rm/2009a/06/125033.htm Remarks at U.S.-India Business Council's 34th Anniversary \"Synergies Summit\"]</ref>\n\n[[File:President Obama, Secretary Clinton, and the Indian Delegation Pose for a Photo (4693387967).jpg|thumb|President Barack Obama, Secretary of State Hillary Clinton, and the Indian delegation at the U.S.-India Strategic Dialogue reception at the Department of State in Washington, D.C., 2010.]]\nIn June 2010, the United States and India formally re-engaged the US-India Strategic Dialogue initiated under President Bush when a large delegation of high-ranking Indian officials, led by External Affairs Minister S.M. Krishna, visited [[Washington, D.C.]] As leader of the US delegation, Secretary of State Clinton lauded India as \"an indispensable partner and a trusted friend\".<ref>https://fas.org/sgp/crs/row/RL33529.pdf</ref> President Obama appeared briefly at a [[United States Department of State]] reception to declare his firm belief that America's relationship with India \"will be one of the defining partnerships of the 21st century.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2010/11/08/remarks-president-joint-session-indian-parliament-new-delhi-india|title=Remarks by the President to the Joint Session of the Indian Parliament in New Delhi, India|publisher=|accessdate=27 September 2014|date=November 8, 2010}}</ref> The Strategic Dialogue produced a joint statement in which the two countries pledged to \"deepen people-to-people, business-to-business, and government-to-government linkages ... for the mutual benefit of both countries and for the promotion of global peace, stability, economic growth and prosperity.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hyderabad.usconsulate.gov/clintonvisit0711.html|title=U.S.-INDIA STRATEGIC DIALOGUE \u2013 Consulate General of the United States Hyderabad, India|publisher=|accessdate=27 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216221924/http://hyderabad.usconsulate.gov/clintonvisit0711.html|archive-date=February 16, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> It outlined extensive bilateral initiatives in each of ten key areas: (1) advancing global security and countering terrorism, (2) disarmament and nonproliferation, (3) trade and economic relations, (4) high technology, (5) energy security, clean energy, and climate change, (6) agriculture, (7) education, (8) health, (9) science and technology, and (10) development.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2011/07/168745.htm|title=U.S.-India Strategic Dialogue Joint Statement|work=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2010, Obama became the second US President (after [[Richard Nixon]] in 1969) to undertake a visit to India in his first term in office. On 8 November, Obama also became the second US President (after Dwight D. Eisenhower in 1959) to ever address a [[joint session]] of the [[Parliament of India]]. In a major policy shift, Obama declared US support for India's [[United Nations Security Council#Permanent members|permanent membership]] on the UN Security Council.<ref name=\"nyt20101108\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20100131/spectrum/main1.htm|title=Richard Nixon visited India in 1969 after becoming the president}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/09/world/asia/09prexy.html |title=Obama Backs India for Seat on Security Council |last=Stolberg |first=Sheryl |date=8 November 2010 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=8 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511143448/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/09/world/asia/09prexy.html |archivedate=May 11, 2011}}</ref> Calling the India\u2013U.S. relationship \"a defining partnership of the 21st century\", he also announced the removal of export control restrictions on several Indian companies, and concluded trade deals worth $10 billion, which are expected to create and/or support 50,000 jobs in the US.<ref name=\"bbc20101108x\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-11712268|title=Obama confirms U.S. strategic shift towards India|last=Reynolds|first=Paul|date=8 November 2010|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=8 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n===== Devyani Khobragade incident =====\n{{Main|Devyani Khobragade incident}}\n\nIn December 2013, [[Devyani Khobragade]], the Deputy Consul General of [[India]] in New York, was arrested and accused by U.S. federal prosecutors of submitting false work visa documents for her housekeeper and paying the housekeeper \"far less than the [[Minimum wage in the United States|minimum legal wage]].\"<ref name=\"Harris\">{{cite news|author=Gardiner Harris|title=Outrage in India, and Retaliation, Over a Female Diplomat's Arrest in New York|date=December 17, 2013|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/18/world/asia/outrage-in-india-over-female-diplomats-arrest-in-new-york.html|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref> The ensuing incident caused protests from the Indian government and a rift in India\u2013United States relations; Indians expressed outrage that Khobragade was strip-searched (a routine practice for all persons arrested by the [[United States Marshals Service|U.S. Marshals Service]]) and held in the general inmate population.<ref name=\"Harris\" /> For example, former Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]] said that Khobragade's treatment was \"deplorable\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/devyani-khobragade-us-india-row-escalates-after-diplomat-complains-about-strip-search-after-arrest|title=Devyani Khobragade: US-India Row Escalates After Diplomat Complains About Strip-Search After Arrest On Visa Fraud|work=International Business Times|accessdate=27 September 2014|date=December 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIndia demanded an apology from the U.S. over her alleged \"humiliation\" and called for the charges to be dropped, which the U.S. declined to do.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-25459805|title=Devyani Khobragade row: US refuses to drop charges| publisher= BBC World News| date=20 December 2013}}</ref> The Indian government retaliated for what it viewed as the mistreatment of its consular official by revoking the ID cards and other privileges of U.S. consular personnel and their families in India and removing security barriers in front of the [[U.S. Embassy in New Delhi]].<ref name=DB4>{{cite news|title=India removes U.S. Embassy security barriers in spat|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/12/18/us-usa-india-diplomat-idUSBRE9BG1A820131218|accessdate=December 29, 2013|agency=Reuters|date=December 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Indian government also blocked non-diplomats from using the American Community Support Association (ACSA) club and American Embassy Club in New Delhi, ordering these social clubs to cease all commercial activities benefiting non-diplomatic personnel by 16 January 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://worldnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2014/01/08/22224237-india-bars-non-diplomats-from-us-embassy-club-amid-escalating-spat?lite |title=India bars non-diplomats from US embassy club amid escalating spat |publisher=NBC News |date=8 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108102933/http://worldnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2014/01/08/22224237-india-bars-non-diplomats-from-us-embassy-club-amid-escalating-spat?lite |archivedate=January 8, 2014 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The ACSA club operates a bar, bowling alley, swimming pool, restaurant, video-rentals club, indoor gym and a beauty parlour within the embassy premises.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/in-anticipation-of-shut-down-us-embassy-had-disabled-acsa-website-days-ago/1216815/|title=In anticipation of shut down, US Embassy had disabled ACSA website days ago|work=The Indian Express |date=8 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-asks-us-embassy-to-stop-commercial-activities/article5552945.ece?homepage=true|title=India asks US Embassy to stop commercial activities|work=The Hindu |date=8 January 2014|location=Chennai, India|first=Sandeep|last=Dikshit}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jan/08/india-us-american-embassy-club-row|title=India cracks down on US embassy club in diplomatic row|work=The Guardian |date=8 January 2014}}</ref> Tax-free import clearances given to US diplomats and consular officials for importing food, alcohol and other domestic items were revoked with immediate effect. U.S. embassy vehicles and staff are no longer immune from penalties for traffic violations. American diplomats were asked to show work contracts of all domestic help (cooks, gardeners, drivers and security staff) employed within their households.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/28/world/asia/india-consular-employee-retaliation.html?_r=0|title=India Finds New Methods to Punish U.S. Diplomats |work=New York Times |date=27 December 2013 |first=Gardiner |last=Harris}}</ref> Indian authorities also conducted an investigation into the [[American Embassy School]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/income-tax-dept-discreetly-probing-us-embassy-school/article1-1182244.aspx|title=I-T dept 'discreetly' probing US embassy school |publisher=Hindustan Times |date=9 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/16/world/asia/indian-school-ensnared-in-us-diplomatic-row.html?hpw&rref=education|title=American Embassy School in India Ensnared in U.S. Diplomatic Spat |work=New York Times |date=16 January 2014 |first1=Gardiner |last1=Harris |first2=Benjamin |last2=Weiser}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/with-charges-dropped-against-diplomat-india-us-relations-start-to-thaw/2014/03/13/89d1651c-aa98-11e3-adbc-888c8010c799_story.html|title=As charges against Devyani Khobragade are dropped, relief and lingering doubts in India|author=Annie Gowen|date=March 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nKhobragade was subject to prosecution at the time of her arrest because she had only [[consular immunity]] (which gives one [[immunity from prosecution]] only for acts committed in connection with official duties) and not the more extensive [[diplomatic immunity]].<ref name=\"Harris\" /><ref name=\"McKelvey\">Tara McKelvey, [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-25458531 Who, What, Why: Does Devyani Khobragade have diplomatic immunity?], BBC News (December 19, 2013).</ref> After her arrest, the Indian government moved Khobragade to the Indian mission to the United Nations, upgrading her status and conferring diplomatic immunity on her; as a result, the federal indictment against Khobragade was dismissed in March 2014, although the door was left open to refiling of charges.<ref>Jonathan Stempel & Shyamantha Asokan, [https://www.reuters.com/article/india-usa-diplomat-idINL2N0M92BW20140313 UPDATE 3-Indian diplomat in U.S. row wins indictment dismissal], Reuters (March 13, 2014).</ref> A new indictment was filed against Khobragade, but by that point she had left the country.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/new-indictment-filed-against-indian-diplomat-devyani-khobragade-in-us-visa-fraud-case/2014/03/14/0074dd80-abb0-11e3-adbc-888c8010c799_story.html New indictment filed against Indian diplomat Devyani Khobragade in U.S. visa-fraud case], ''Washington Post'' (March 14, 2014).</ref> (In an effort to resolve the dispute, the U.S. State Department had told Khobragade to leave the country).<ref name=\"BarryTires\" />\n\nNancy J. Powell, the U.S. ambassador to India, resigned following the incident, which was widely seen by India \"as fallout from the imbroglio.\"<ref name=\"BarryTires\">Ellen Barry, [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/21/world/asia/india-tires-of-diplomatic-rift-over-arrest.html India Tires of Diplomatic Rift Over Arrest of Devyani Khobragade], ''New York Times'' (December 20, 2014).</ref> Some commentators suggested that the incident and response could lead to wider damage in U.S.\u2013India relations.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/US-refuses-to-talk-China-with-India/articleshow/30533211.cms?intenttarget=no|title=US refuses to talk China with India|work=Times of India |date=17 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/india-moves-to-end-expat-privileges-at-us-club-sign-of-anger-at-diplomats-arrest-in-ny/2014/01/08/761554d6-7850-11e3-a647-a19deaf575b3_story.html|title=India targets expatriates' privileges at U.S. club amid dispute over diplomat's arrest|work=Washington Post |date=8 January 2014|first1=Rama|last1=Lakshmi|first2=Karen|last2=DeYoung}}</ref> Former Finance Minister [[Yashwant Sinha]] called for the arrest of [[LGBT rights in India|same-sex companions]] of US diplomats, citing the [[Supreme Court of India]]'s upholding of [[Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code]] whereby homosexuality is illegal in India.<ref>{{cite news|last=Buncombe|first=Andrew|title=India-US row over arrest of diplomat Devyani Khobragade in New York escalates|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/indiaus-row-over-arrest-of-diplomat-devyani-khobragade-in-new-york-escalates-9011080.html|newspaper=The Independent|date=December 17, 2013|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Punish US diplomats with same sex companions: Yashwant Sinha|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/punish-us-diplomats-with-same-sex-companions-yashwant-sinha-113121700928_1.html|newspaper=Business Standard|date=December 17, 2013}}</ref> Former State Department legal advisor [[John Bellinger]] questioned whether the decision to arrest and detain Khobragade was \"wise policy ... even if technically permissible\" under the [[Vienna Convention on Consular Relations]], while [[Robert D. Blackwill]], the former U.S. ambassador to India from 2001 to 2003, said the incident was \"stupid.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cfr.org/india/new-indian-government/p33026 |publisher=Council on Foreign Relations (CFR) |title=The New Indian Government (Video of Panel Discussion) |date=May 28, 2014 |access-date=May 30, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531090712/http://www.cfr.org/india/new-indian-government/p33026 |archive-date=May 31, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Blackwill|first=Robert|title=US To Warm Up To India After Prime Minister Modi's Win|url=http://www.bernama.com.my/bernama/v7/wn/newsworld.php?id=1042328|newspaper=Bernama|date=May 29, 2014|accessdate=May 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531105154/http://www.bernama.com.my/bernama/v7/wn/newsworld.php?id=1042328|archive-date=May 31, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nevertheless, within a year of the incident, U.S.-India relations were warming again, as U.S. President Obama visited India in January 2015.<ref name=\"BarryTires\" />\n\nSpeaking at [[Harvard Law School]] in 2014, U.S. Attorney in Manhattan [[Preet Bharara]], in the Khobragade case, said: \"(It was) not the crime of the century but a serious crime nonetheless, that is why the State Department opened the case, that is why the State Department investigated it. That is why career agents in the State Department asked career prosecutors in my office to approve criminal charges.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/preet-bharara-talks-khobragade-case-at-harvard-law-school/1/364729.html|title=Preet Bharara talks Khobragade case at Harvard Law School |work=India Today |date=1 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=DB3>{{cite news|title=Arrest, strip-search of Indian diplomat in New York triggers uproar|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/12/17/politics/india-us-diplomat/|publisher=CNN|date=December 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/international/bharara-talks-khobragade-case-114060100160_1.html|title=Bharara talks Khobragade case |publisher=Business Standard & Press Trust of India |date=2 June 2014}}</ref> Bharara, who was born in India, said that he was upset by attacks on him in the Indian press.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/bharara-says-upset-by-criticism/|title=Bharara says upset by criticism |work=Indian Express |date=1 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nKhobragade was originally a highly sympathetic figure in India, as Indians viewed her arrest as an affront to national dignity. Opinions in India shifted, however, after Khobragade was the subject of two inquiries by the Indian government.<ref name=\"BarryTires\" /><ref>[[Sandip Roy (author)|Sandip Roy]], [http://www.firstpost.com/india/pick-symbols-of-national-pride-carefully-what-misadventures-of-khobragade-has-taught-india-2354484.html Pick symbols of national pride carefully: What (mis)adventures of Khobragade has taught India], ''First Post'' (July 22, 2015).</ref> One internal investigation found that Khobragade had violated regulations \"by failing to inform the government that her children had been issued [[American passport]]s\" and resulted in Khobragade being administratively disciplined; a second inquiry was held into Khobragade's series of interviews about the case, undertaken without authorization from the Ministry of External Affairs.<ref name=\"BarryTires\" />\n\n==== Relationship between US Government and Chief Minister of Gujarat Narendra Modi (2001\u20132014) ====\n[[Narendra Modi]], the Chief Minister of Gujarat between 2001 and 2014, became the Prime Minister of India on 26 May 2014 after the [[BJP|Bharatiya Janata Party]] decisively won the [[2014 Indian general election|2014 Indian General Elections]]. The US Government completely failed to anticipate the political rise of Narendra Modi to the office of Prime Minister of India.\n\nSectarian violence during the 2002 Gujarat riots damaged relations between the US Government and Narendra Modi, the then incumbent Chief Minister of Gujarat. Human rights activists accused Modi of fostering anti-Muslim violence. New-York based NGO [[Human Rights Watch]], in their 2002 report directly implicated Gujarat state officials in the violence against Muslims.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. Evangelicals, Indian Expats Teamed Up to Push Through Modi Visa Ban|url=http://india.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/12/05/u-s-evangelicals-indian-expats-teamed-up-to-push-through-modi-visa-ban/?_r=0|work=New York Times|date=5 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, a Special Investigation Team (SIT) appointed by the Indian Supreme Court found no \"prosecutable evidence\" against Modi.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.voanews.com/content/india-swears-in-pm-as-south-asian-leaders-watch-/1922865.html|title=India Swears In PM as South Asian Leaders Watch |publisher=Voice of America (VOA) |date=19 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/710233/washington-clears-modi-for-visit-after-ban/|title=Washington clears Modi for visit after ban |work=The Express Tribune |date=19 May 2014}}</ref> The Supreme Court of India absolved Narendra Modi of any criminal wrongdoing during the 2002 Gujarat riots.\n\nPrior to Narendra Modi becoming the Prime Minister of India, the US Government had made it known that Modi as [[Chief Minister of Gujarat]] would not be permitted to travel to the US. Michael Kugelman of the [[Wilson Center]] opined that although technically speaking there was no US 'visa ban' from 2005 to 2014, the US government policy of considering Modi as ''persona non grata'' had resulted in a ''de facto'' travel-ban.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/05/four-misconceptions-about-narendra-modi/|title=Four Misconceptions About Narendra Modi |work=The Diplomat |date=28 May 2013}}</ref> After the US revoked his existing B1/B2 visa in 2005 and refused to accept his application for an A2 visa, the US State Department affirmed that the visa policy remained unchanged : \"(Mr Modi) is welcome to apply for a visa and await a review like any other applicant\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/dpb/2013/09/214231.htm#INDIA|title=Daily Press Briefing: Revoked US visa of Narendra Modi |publisher=US Department of State |date=13 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://carnegieendowment.org/2014/05/12/productive-but-joyless-narendra-modi-and-u.s.-india-relations/han1|title=Productive but Joyless? Narendra Modi and U.S.-India Relations |publisher=Carnegie South Asia Program |date=12 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nExploring opportunities on how to move the relationship out of a state of morose, Lisa Curtis, senior research fellow for South Asia in the Asian Studies Center of the [[Heritage Foundation]], says that \"the U.S. must first signal its willingness and commitment to collaborating with the new government\u2014and that it will not dwell on the controversy of the 2002 Gujarat riots, which led the U.S. to revoke Modi's visa in 2005.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.heritage.org/research/reports/2014/06/after-the-election-opportunity-for-revitalizing-usindia-relations|title=After the Election: Opportunity for Revitalizing U.S.\u2013India Relations |publisher=The Heritage Foundation |date=2 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 June 2014, [[Robert Blackwill]], the former Coordinator for Strategic Planning and Deputy US National Security Advisor during the presidency of George W. Bush, spoke at length about India\u2013U.S. relations and said : \"Mr Modi is a determined leader. He is candid and frank. I also worked with him during the Gujarat earthquake when I was posted as (the US) ambassador to India. ... It was mistake by the current Obama administration to delay engagement with Mr Modi. I do not know why they did so but definitely, this did not help in building relationship. ... The old formula and stereotypes will not work if the US administration wants to engage with Mr Modi. The Indian prime minister is candid, direct and smart. He speaks his mind. The US administration also has to engage in candid conversation when Mr Modi meets President Obama later this year. They have to do something innovative to engage with him.\" <ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-06-11/news/50508526_1_narendra-modi-south-china-sea-president-obama|title=Obama should hold candid talks to engage Modi: Robert Blackwill |work=Economic Times |date=11 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===== 2005 denial of visa application and revocation of visa =====\nIn 2005, the US Department of State used a 1998 International Religious Freedom Act (IRFA) provision to revoke Modi's tourist/business visa citing section 212 (a) (2) (g) of the US Immigration and Nationality Act.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2005/43643.htm|title=Denial of Visa Application and Revocation of Visa for Gujarati Chief Minister Narendra Modi |publisher=US Department of State |date=18 March 2005}}</ref> The IRFA provision \"makes any foreign government official who 'was responsible for or directly carried out, at any time, particularly severe violations of religious freedom' ineligible for a visa to the United States.\"\n\n[[David C. Mulford]], the US Ambassador to India from 2003 to 2009, justified the rejection of a diplomatic visa to Modi in a statement released on 21 March 2005 stating that the US State Department re-affirmed the original decision to revoke Modi's tourist/business visa to which India's highest judiciary abstained all the charges from Modi later on the particular issue:<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/I-am-sad-about-Gujarat-riots-but-have-no-guilt-Narendra-Modi-in-biography/articleshow/32675740.cms|title= Indian courts crushes inept charges|work=Times of India|date=25 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>This decision applies to Mr. Narendra Modi only. It is based on the fact that, as head of the State government in Gujarat between February 2002 and May 2002, he was responsible for the performance of state institutions at that time. The State Department's detailed views on this matter are included in its annual Country Reports on Human Rights Practices and the International Religious Freedom Report. Both reports document the violence in Gujarat from February 2002 to May 2002 and cite the Indian National Human Rights Commission report, which states there was \"a comprehensive failure on the part of the state government to control the persistent violation of rights of life, liberty, equality, and dignity of the people of the state.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://2001-2009.state.gov/p/sca/rls/rm/2005/43701.htm|title=Statement by David C. Mulford, U.S. Ambassador to India regarding Issue of Gujarat Chief Minister Narendra Modi's Visa Status |publisher=US Department of State |date=21 March 2005}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nModi remains the only person ever to be banned to travel to the United States of America under the International Religious Freedom Act (IRFA) provision of US Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) due to political interest.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303380004579520041301275638|title=Why Narendra Modi Was Banned From the U.S. |work=Wall Street Journal |date=2 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/indiahome/indianews/article-2641938/WHIPLASH-U-S-apologise-visa-ban.html|title=U.S. must now apologise for Modi's visa ban |work=Daily Mail |date=28 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nRobert Blackwill, former US ambassador to India opined: \"I think it was a serious mistake on the part of the last (Bush) administration to do that (deny Modi a visa) and the current (Obama) administration to keep it in place ... all the way till the 2014 Indian elections\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/xvYGXVknujGAWxkkzdyaBJ/Ahead-of-ModiObama-meet-India-and-US-seek-to-strengthen-bi.html|title=Ahead of Modi-Obama meet, India and US seek to strengthen ties |publisher=Live Mint |date=10 June 2014}}</ref> Blackwill highlighted the decision to deny Modi a visa as \"absolutely unique\" involving private political interest saying that the people who made the decision \"thought, it's pretty safe, because, he's never going to be Prime Minister\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sirfnews.com/world/india-sought-out-ally-or-partner-for-all,-with-us-regretting-its-excesses/917-india-sought-out-ally-or-partner-for-all,-with-us-regretting-its-excesses.html|title=India sought out ally or partner for all, with US regretting its excesses|publisher=SIRF News|date=21 June 2014|access-date=June 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140725171013/http://www.sirfnews.com/world/india-sought-out-ally-or-partner-for-all,-with-us-regretting-its-excesses/917-india-sought-out-ally-or-partner-for-all,-with-us-regretting-its-excesses.html|archive-date=July 25, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Modi was found not guilty of the charges by India's judiciary.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-supreme-court-rejects-plea-questioning-clean-chit-to-narendra-modi-on-role-in-2002-gujarat-riots-1977348|title=Modi gets clean chit from supreme court|publisher=DNA|date=11 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[R. Nicholas Burns|Nicholas Burns]], former U.S. Undersecretary of State for Political Affairs from 2005 to 2008, has spoken about the visa denial by saying: \"Bush administration officials, including me, believed this to be the right decision at the time.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/141851/nicholas-burns/passage-to-india|title=Passage to India |publisher=Council on Foreign Relations |date=1 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/01/barack-obama-narendra-modi-india-trip-114576_Page2.html|title=Barack Obama's risky bet on Narendra Modi|author=Edward-Isaac Dovere|authorlink=Edward-Isaac Dovere|date=25 January 2015|work=POLITICO|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref> and has opined that \"Now that it looks like Modi will become prime minister, it's reasonable for the Obama administration to say it's been 12 years [since the 2002 riots], and we'll be happy to deal with him\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2014/05/03/why-the-u-s-banned-narendra-modi/|title=Why The U.S. Banned Narendra Modi|author=James Mann|work=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=2 April 2016|date=May 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===== 2009 USCIRF visa black-list =====\nIn 2009, the US Commission for International Religious Freedom (USCIRF) report <ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.state.gov/md51618.htm|title=International Religious Freedom Report 2005|publisher=U.S. Department of State|date=8 Nov 2005|access-date=June 3, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819184412/http://m.state.gov/md51618.htm|archive-date=August 19, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> after ignoring the views and decision of independent body (SIT) set up by India's highest judiciary<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/topic/clean-chit-to-Narendra-Modi|title=clean chit to Narendra Modi|work=The Times of India|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> vehemently alleged that there was \"significant evidence\" linking Narendra Modi to communal riots in the state in 2002 and asked the Obama administration to continue the policy of preventing him from travelling to the United States of America .<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.uscirf.gov/reports-briefs/annual-report/2013-annual-report|title=USCIRF's 2013 Annual Report |publisher=US Commission for International Religious Freedom (USCIRF) |date=1 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/fareed-zakaria-with-modi-heading-to-victory-in-india-us-policy-needs-to-change/2014/05/15/830a8b0e-dc80-11e3-8009-71de85b9c527_story.html|title=U.S. policy on India, and Modi, needs to change |work=Washington Post |date=16 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Obama administration maintained the 2005 decision taken by the George W. Bush administration to deny Narendra Modi entry into the United States of America.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/US-panel-calls-for-continued-ban-on-Narendra-Modi-slams-India-on-religious-freedom/articleshow/19823171.cms|title=US panel calls for continued ban on Narendra Modi, slams India on religious freedom |work=Times of India |date=1 May 2013}}</ref> The US Government says that Modi can circumvent the USCIRF sanctions regime by visiting Washington on a Heads of government A1-visa as long as he is the Prime Minister of India.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/05/16/politics/modi-us-visa/|title=Previously denied a visa, new Indian PM 'will be welcomed' to U.S. |publisher=CNN |date=16 May 2013}}</ref> According to US State Department Spokesperson, Jen Psaki : \"US law exempts foreign government officials, including heads of state and heads of government from certain potential inadmissibility grounds\". The visa refusal came after some Indian-American groups and human rights organizations with political view campaigned against Modi, including the [[Coalition Against Genocide]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rajghatta|first1=C.|title=In 'reset' phone call, Obama erases decade of stigma around Modi|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/lok-sabha-elections-2014/news/In-reset-phone-call-Obama-erases-decade-of-stigma-around-Modi/articleshow/35271636.cms|accessdate=3 June 2014|work=Times of India|date=18 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== BJP government (2014\u2013present) ===\n\nAt present, India and the US share an extensive and expanding cultural, strategic, military, and economic relationship<ref>Teresita C. Schaffer, ''India and the United States in the 21st Century: Reinventing Partnership'' (2010)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/row/RL34161.pdf|title=India-U.S. Economic and Trade Relations|author=|date= |publisher=Federation of American Scientists|accessdate=March 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comw.org/pda/0603india.html|title=The Evolving India-U.S. Strategic Relationship: A Compendium of Articles and Analyses|publisher=|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Indo-U.S. Relations: Moving Beyond the Plateau|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2014/07/30/indo-u-s-relations-moving-beyond-the-plateau/|work=Foreign Policy|date=30 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=21st Century is India's Century: IBM Chief Virginia Rometty|url=http://profit.ndtv.com/news/corporates/article-21st-century-is-indias-century-ibm-chief-virginia-rometty-781473|publisher=NDTV|date=14 July 2015}}</ref> which is in the phase of implementing ''[[Confidence and security-building measures|confidence building measures]]'' (CBM) to overcome the legacy of ''[[Trust management (managerial science)|trust deficit]]'' \u2013 brought about by adversarial US foreign policies <ref>{{cite news|title=Beyond the immediate present|url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/beyond-the-immediate-present/article6821491.ece|work=The Hindu|date=26 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Collateral Damage|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/29/books/review/the-blood-telegram-by-gary-j-bass.html?_r=0|work=New York Times|date=27 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nixon's dislike of 'witch' Indira|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4633263.stm|publisher=BBC World Service|date=29 June 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Clinton Imposes Full Sanctions On India|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/specials/clinton-imposes-full-sanctions-on-india-198051401086_1.html|publisher=Business Standard|date=14 May 1998}}</ref> and multiple instances of technology denial <ref>{{cite news|title=India overcame US sanctions to develop cryogenic engine|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/India-overcame-US-sanctions-to-develop-cryogenic-engine/articleshow/28449360.cms?referral=PM|work=Times of India|date=6 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=How Kargil spurred India to design own GPS|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/science/How-Kargil-spurred-India-to-design-own-GPS/articleshow/33254691.cms|publisher=Times of India|date=5 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=India working on building fastest supercomputer|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/441216/india-working-building-fastest-supercomputer.html|publisher=Deccan Herald|date=13 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Indian scientists thwart Western embargo on manufacture of carbon composites |url=http://www.indiaenvironmentportal.org.in/content/4374/indian-scientists-thwart-western-embargo-on-manufacture-of-carbon-composites/|publisher=Centre for Science and Environment |date=30 August 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Wassenaar effect|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/opinion/the-wassenaar-effect/article7612180.ece|publisher=Hindu Business Line|date=3 September 2015}}</ref> \u2013 which have plagued the relationship over several decades.<ref>{{cite news|title=The geopolitical context of India-US ties|url=http://zeenews.india.com/exclusive/the-geopolitical-context-of-india-us-ties_1474021.html|publisher=Zee News|date=23 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The geopolitical context of India-US ties|url=http://zeenews.india.com/exclusive/the-geopolitical-context-of-india-us-ties_1474021.html|publisher=Zee News|date=23 September 2014}}</ref> Unrealistic expectations after the conclusion of the 2008 [[U.S.\u2013India Civil Nuclear Agreement]] (which underestimated negative public opinion regarding the long-term viability of nuclear power generation and civil-society endorsement for contractual guarantees on safeguards and liability) has given way to pragmatic realism and refocus on areas of cooperation which enjoy favourable political and electoral consensus.\n\nKey recent developments include the rapid growth of India's economy, closer ties between the Indian and American industries especially in the Information and communications technology (ICT), engineering and medical sectors, an informal ''[[Entente (type of alliance)|entente]]'' to manage an increasingly assertive [[China]], robust cooperation on counter-terrorism, the deterioration of [[U.S.-Pakistan relations]], easing of export controls over dual-use goods & technologies (99% of licenses applied for are now approved),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/articleshow/54830169.cms |title=US rules out treaty alliance with India, says that era is over |date=13 October 2016 |website=India Times |accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref> and reversal of long-standing American opposition to India's strategic program.\n\nIncome creation in the USA through knowledge-based employment by Asian Indians has outpaced every other ethnic group according to U.S. Census data.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/usas-best-indian-americans-top-community/85882-2.html |title=USA\u00c3\u00a2\u00ef\u00bf\u00bd\u00ef\u00bf\u00bds best: Indian Americans top community \u2013 World \u2013 IBNLive |publisher=Ibnlive.in.com |date=2009-02-20 |accessdate=2013-02-07}}</ref> Growing financial and political clout of the affluent ''[[Indian American|Asian Indian]]'' diaspora is noteworthy. Indian American households are the most prosperous in the US with a median revenue of US$100,000, followed by Chinese Americans at US$65000. The average household revenue in the USA is US$50000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.voanews.com/all-about-america/2015/05/08/this-us-ethnic-group-makes-the-most-money/|title=Richest Ethnicities in US|date=3 October 2015|work=The Economist}}</ref>\n\nUS and India continue to differ on issues ranging from trade to civil liberties. The Indian Home Ministry, through an affidavit submitted to the Delhi High Court on 13 February 2015, claimed that Country Reports on Rights & Practices have become instruments of foreign policy: \"The US, UK and EU have clearly mentioned in government documents and pronouncements that these reports are made for the purpose of their being used as instruments of foreign policy.\" The affidavit also claimed that the reports by US, UK and European Parliament were biased since they \"do not provide opportunity to the Government of India or the local embassy/high commission to record their opinion and are heavily biased against the targeted country\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Govt defends activist Priya Pillai's offloading, slams west's rights reports|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Govt-defends-activist-Priya-Pillais-offloading-slams-wests-rights-reports/articleshow/46257518.cms|work=Times of India|date=16 February 2015}}</ref> The 2014 State Department's annual [[Trafficking in Persons Report|Trafficking in Persons (TIP) report]] appeared to classify the Khobragade incident as an example of human trafficking, stating: \"An Indian consular officer at the New York consulate was indicted in December 2013 for visa fraud related to her alleged exploitation of an Indian domestic worker.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/world/devyani-khobragade-featured-in-us-human-trafficking-report/article6134380.ece|title=Devyani Khobragade featured in U.S. human trafficking report |work=The Hindu |date=21 June 2014}}</ref> In response, India has shown no urgency to allow visits to India by the newly appointed US anti-people trafficking ambassador [[Susan P. Coppedge]] and the US special envoy for LGBT rights Randy Berry. Under [[Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code]] homosexuality was illegal in India. Indian Ambassador to the US, Arun K. Singh reiterated India's commitment to work within an international framework to tackle the problem of trafficking but rejected any \"unilateral assessments\" by another country saying \"We will never accept it\" and downplayed the importance of the visits: \"When you ask a U.S. official when somebody will be given a visa, they always say 'we will assess when visa is applied for.' ... I can do no better than to reiterate the U.S. position.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=India blocks visits by U.S. officials despite warmer ties|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/11/20/us-usa-india-idUSKCN0T92YI20151120|publisher=Reuters|date=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, the Obama administration notified the US Congress that it intended to provide Pakistan eight nuclear-capable F-16 fighters and assorted military goods including eight [[AN/APG-68]](V)9 airborne radars and eight ALQ-211(V)9 electronic warfare suites<ref>{{cite news|title=US to give Pakistan eight F-16s, India fumes|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/US-to-give-Pakistan-eight-F-16s-India-fumes/articleshow/50979409.cms|work=Times of India|date=14 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=India disappointed by U.S. sale of F-16 fighters to Pakistan|url=http://www.militarytimes.com/story/military/2016/02/14/india-disappointed-us-sale-f-16-fighters-pakistan/80373748/|work=Military Times|date=14 February 2016}}</ref> despite strong reservations from US lawmakers regarding the transfer of any nuclear weapons capable platforms to Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|title=US shouldn't sell nuclear-armed version of F-16 to Pak: Republican leadership|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us/US-shouldnt-sell-nuclear-armed-version-of-F-16-to-Pak-Republican-leadership/articleshow/49826432.cms|work=Times of India|date=18 November 2015}}</ref> Shashi Tharoor, an elected representative from the Congress party in India, questioned the substance of India\u2013U.S. ties: \"I am very disappointed to hear this news. The truth is that continuing to escalate the quality of arms available to an irresponsible regime that has sent terrorists to India, and in the name of anti-terrorism, is cynicism of the highest order\".<ref>{{cite news|title=F-16 to Pak calls into question substance of Indo-US ties: Tharoor|url=http://www.sify.com/news/f-16-to-pak-calls-into-question-substance-of-indo-us-ties-tharoor-news-national-qcnshAdbebhhe.html|publisher=Sify News|date=14 Feb 2016}}</ref> The Indian Government summoned the US Ambassador to India to convey its disapproval regarding the sale of F-16 fighter jets to Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|title=F-16, Pervez Musharraf pour cold water on Indo-Pak dialogue|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/F-16-Pervez-Musharraf-pour-cold-water-on-Indo-Pak-dialogue/articleshow/50988622.cms|work=Times of India|date=15 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Indian ambassador to the U.S. [[Navtej Sarna]] hosted a reception for the [[National Governors Association]] (NGA), which was attended by the Governors of 25 states and senior representatives of 3 more states. This was the first time such an event has occurred. Explaining the reason for the gathering, Virginia Governor and NGA Chair [[Terry McAuliffe]] stated that \"India is America's greatest strategic partner\". He further added, \"We clearly understand the strategic importance of India, of India\u2013U.S. relations. As we grow our 21st century economy, India has been so instrumental in helping us build our technology, medical professions. We recognise a country that has been such a close strategic ally of the US. That's why we the Governors are here tonight.\" McAuliffe, who has visited India 15 times, also urged other Governors to visit the country with trade delegations to take advantage of opportunities.<ref>{{cite web|title=India is Americas greatest strategic partner: top US Governor|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/news/current-affairs/india-is-americas-greatest-strategic-partner-top-us-governor_8555021.html|website=Money Control|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Threat of sanctions against India ====\nIn October 2018, India inked the historic agreement worth US$5.43 billion  with [[Russia]] to procure four [[S-400 Triumf]] surface-to-air missile defence system, the most powerful [[Missile defence|missile defence system]] in the world ignoring America's [[Countering America's Adversaries Through Sanctions Act|CAATSA act]]. The U.S. threatened India with sanctions over India's decision to buy the S-400 missile defense system from Russia.<ref>{{cite news |title=India, facing sanctions for Russian arms deals, says it wants to pivot spending to the US |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/23/india-to-pivot-spending-to-the-us-amid-russia-arms-deals-sanctions.html |work=CNBC |date=23 May 2019}}</ref> The United States also threatened India with sanctions over India's decision to buy [[Petroleum industry in Iran|oil from Iran]].<ref>{{cite news |title=US threatens India with CAATSA if it continues to purchase fuel from Iran |url=https://in.news.yahoo.com/us-threatens-india-caatsa-continues-044500451.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmN6Lw&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAKaVNQwtIyx5VcUJEIUOfD9ctVgk-FwVXbjLNopQAhvSqfnLaEkMIdy1Nu6FTMpBnOLPId5gx7c19HfIWMX_OVDjHVUdaYxX2kipal0yFoOvqhbCEtohboYjB56mlE0YSGPqhTzEsv1L_4rR0_JSRyFuK2AdXq6NVhBBRoR1VZ8r |work=Yahoo News |date=October 12, 2018}}</ref> According to the President of the U.S.-India Strategic Partnership Forum (USISPF), Mukesh Aghi: \"sanctions would have a disastrous effect on U.S.-India relations for decades to come. In India\u2019s eyes, the United States would once again be regarded as untrustworthy.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Why Punishing India on Russia Would Be a Mistake for the United States |url=https://thediplomat.com/2018/05/why-punishing-india-on-russia-would-be-a-mistake-for-the-united-states/ |work=The Diplomat |date=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Relationship between U.S. Government and Prime Minister of India Narendra Modi (2014 onwards) ====\n[[File:President Trump and the First Lady in India (49583481291).jpg|thumb|U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] and Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] at [[Namaste Trump]] rally in [[Ahmedabad]], India on February 24, 2020]]\n===== Modi's visit to America, 2015 =====\nDuring the run-off to the 2014 Indian general election, there was wide-ranging scepticism regarding the future of the India\u2013U.S. strategic relationship. Narendra Modi, whose US visa had been revoked while he was the [[Chief Minister of Gujarat]], had been boycotted by US officials for almost a decade<ref>{{cite news|title=No entry for Modi into US: visa denied|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/No-entry-for-Modi-into-US-visa-denied/articleshow/1055543.cms|work=The Times of India|date=18 March 2006\n|accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref> for his alleged role in the [[2002 Gujarat riots]].<ref name=WSJ-visa>{{cite news|last1=Mann|first1=James|title=Why Narendra Modi Was Banned From the U.S.|url=https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303380004579520041301275638?mg=reno64-wsj|accessdate=22 September 2014|work=Wall Street Journal|date=2 May 2014}}</ref> However, sensing Modi's inevitable victory well before the election, the [[United States Ambassador to India|US Ambassabor]] [[Nancy Powell]] had reached out to him. Moreover, following his 2014 election as the Prime Minister of India [[Presidency of Barack Obama|President Obama]] congratulated him over telephone and invited him to visit the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/05/16/readout-president-s-call-prime-ministerial-candidate-narendra-modi-india|title=Readout of the President's Call with Prime Ministerial Candidate Narendra Modi of India|publisher=Whitehouse.gov|date=May 16, 2014|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"newyorker-may14\">{{cite news|last=Cassidy|first=John|title=What Does Modi's Victory Mean for the World?|url=https://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/johncassidy/2014/05/narendra-modi-india-prime-minister-victory.html|accessdate=21 May 2014|newspaper=[[The New Yorker]]|date=16 May 2014}}</ref> US Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] visited New Delhi on 1 August to prepare the grounds for Modi's first ever US visit as Prime Minister. In September 2014, days  before visiting the US in an interview to [[CNN]]'s [[Fareed Zakaria]], Modi said that \"India and the United States are bound together, by history and culture\" but acknowledged that there have been \"ups and downs\" in relations.<ref name=CNN-fareed>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2014/09/21/what-does-modis-cnn-interview-say-about-indias-relationship-with-the-u-s/|title=What Does Modi's CNN Interview Say About India's Relationship With the U.S.?|accessdate=22 September 2014|work=Wall Street Journal|date=21 September 2014}}</ref> Modi travelled to US from 27\u201330 September 2014,<ref name=hectic>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/narendra-modi-has-hectic-schedule-lined-up-for-maiden-us-trip/articleshow/42122631.cms|title=Narendra Mosi has hectic schedule lined up for maiden US trip |newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]|date=2014-09-11|accessdate=2014-09-11|last1=Sharma |first1=Ravi Teja }}</ref> beginning with his maiden address in the [[sixty-ninth session of the United Nations General Assembly|United Nations general assembly]] followed by attending a gala public reception by the Indian American community in New York's [[Madison Square Garden]] before heading Washington, D.C. for the bilateral talk with Obama. While there, Modi also met several American business leaders and invited them to join his ambitious [[Make in India]] program in a bid to make India a manufacturing hub.<ref name=gmodi>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/sep/28/narendra-modi-india-new-york-prime-minister|title=US turns on charm as Narendra Modi roadshow rolls into New York|accessdate=|last=Burke|first=Jason|date=September 28, 2014|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=nytmodi>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/28/world/asia/narendra-modi-madison-square-garden-united-states-indian-diaspora.html|title=Indian Leader Narendra Modi, Once Unwelcome in U.S., Gets Rock Star Reception|accessdate=|last=Sinha|first=Shreeya|date=September 27, 2014|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref name=wpmodi>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/indias-modi-begins-rock-star-like-us-tour/2014/09/26/eeabe78b-9327-4643-a131-33ab5c59174a_story.html|title=India's Modi begins rock star-like U.S. tour|accessdate=|last=Gowen|first=Annie|date=September 26, 2014|work=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n===== Barack Obama's visit to India, 2015 =====\nPresident [[Barack Obama]] became the first US president to be the chief guest of the [[Republic Day (India)|66th Republic Day]] celebrations of India held on 26 January 2015.<ref name=Reuters_1>{{cite news|title=Obama to be chief guest at Republic Day celebrations|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2014/11/21/usa-obama-india-idINKCN0J51PA20141121|accessdate=11 January 2015|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=11 January 2015}}</ref> India and the US held their first ever bilateral dialogue on the UN and multilateral issues in the spirit of the \"Delhi Declaration of Friendship\" that strengthens and expands the two countries' relationship as part of the Post-2015 Development Agenda.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/india-us-hold-first-ever-bilateral-dialogue-un-multilateral-issues-2108019.html |title=India, US hold first ever bilateral dialogue on UN, multilateral issues |publisher=Firstpost |date=2015-02-19 |accessdate=2015-12-30}}</ref>\n\nThe conspicuous absence of major announcements, a key indicator of the state of US relations with the host country, led political commentators in both countries to highlight the confidence-building aspects of the visit<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/india-us-ties-still-problematic-115030301314_1.html|title=India-US ties still problematic|author=Nayanima Basu|date=3 March 2015|publisher=|accessdate=2 April 2016|newspaper=Business Standard India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stories.illinoisstate.edu/university/media-relations/reactions-obamas-visit-to-india-opens-doors/|title=Reactions: Obama's visit to India opens doors, leaves questions \u2013 Illinois State University News|author=Rachel Hatch|date=3 February 2015|work=Illinois State University News|accessdate=2 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fletcher.tufts.edu/News-and-Media/2015/01/27/Chai-and-cha-cha-cha-obamas-visit-to-india-Bhaskar-Chakravorti|title=Chai and Cha Cha Cha: Op-ed on Obama's Visit to India by Dean Chakravorti in Indian Express \u2013 Tufts Fletcher School|publisher=|accessdate=2 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117182733/http://fletcher.tufts.edu/News-and-Media/2015/01/27/Chai-and-cha-cha-cha-obamas-visit-to-india-Bhaskar-Chakravorti|archive-date=January 17, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/us-lawmakers-laud-progress-in-us-india-partnership-115022800143_1.html|title=US lawmakers laud progress in US-India partnership|author=IANS|date=28 February 2015|publisher=|accessdate=2 April 2016|newspaper=Business Standard India}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-opinion/going-beyond-bonhomie/article6813338.ece|title=Going beyond bonhomie|author=M.K. Narayanan|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=2 April 2016|date=January 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===== Modi's visit to America, 2015 =====\nPrime Minister Narendra Modi toured the [[Silicon Valley]] and met with entrepreneurs \u2013 several of whom are persons of Indian origin \u2013 involved in successful microelectronics, digital communications and biotechnology start-ups to promote the NDA government's ''[[Make in India]]'' initiative.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mr. Modi in Silicon Valley|url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/editorial/mr-modi-in-silicon-valley/article7699143.ece|publisher=The Hindu|date=29 September 2015}}</ref> Modi left the U.S. West Coast and travelled to New York for the 2015 UN General Assembly meeting where he had bilateral discussions with US President Barack Obama.\n\n===== Modi's visit to America, 2016 =====\n[[File:The Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi meeting the President of United States of America (USA), Mr. Barack Obama in Oval Office, at White House, in Washington DC, USA on June 07, 2016 (9).jpg|thumb|right|Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] meeting President [[Barack Obama]] in the [[Oval Office]], at the [[White House]], in Washington DC, USA on June 07, 2016.]]\nPrime Minister Narendra Modi while visiting the United States addressed a joint session of Congress highlighting the common traits of both democracies and long-term friendship between the two countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/prime-minister-narendra-modi-us-congress-speech-2842046/|title=PM Narendra Modi's speech in US Congress: Read the full text|date=2016-06-09|access-date=2016-07-30}}</ref> In a speech lasting more than 45 minutes, Mr. Modi drew on parallels between the two countries and addressed a variety of issues where the two countries have worked together in the past and where the future course of action would lie.<ref>{{Citation|last=PMO India|title=FULL SPEECH: PM addresses joint meeting of U.S. Congress in Washington DC|date=2016-06-08|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mEYklHRnovg|accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n\n===== Modi's visit to America, 2017 =====\nOn June 26 2017, Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] visited the United States and met US President [[Donald Trump]].\nOn 8 November 2017, US has announced a grant of nearly US$500,000 for organisations which can come up with ideas and projects to promote religious freedom in India and [[Sri Lanka]].\n\n===== Modi's visit to America, 2019 =====\nIn September 2019, Modi visited Houston and he addressed a large Indian American contingent in the Houston NRG stadium. Along with President Trump, he reaffirmed Indian American ties, with an emphasis on increased military cooperation with the initiation of the [[Tiger Triumph]] exercises.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/20/world/asia/india-military-exercises-trump.html|title=U.S.-India Defense Ties Grow Closer as Shared Concerns in Asia Loom|last=Montague|first=Zach|date=2019-11-20|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-12-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===== Trump's visit to India, 2020 =====\n[[File:President Trump and the First Lady in India (49584141701).jpg|thumb|PM Modi gifts replica of [[Mahatma Gandhi]]'s [[three wise monkeys]] to President Trump]]\nIn February 2020, US President Donald Trump visited India. He addressed people in an event \"[[Namaste Trump]]\" at [[Sardar Patel Stadium]], [[Ahmedabad]]. In his maiden visit to India, both nations significantly ramp up bilateral relations mainly in strategic ties and [https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/donald-trump-india-visit-us-president-donald-trumps-visit-to-india-10-points-2184569 defense].<ref>{{cite news |title=In India, Trump validates Modi\u2019s divisive agenda |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/02/24/india-trump-validates-modis-divisive-agenda/ |work=The Washington Post |date=February 24, 2020}}</ref> \n\nTrump's first official visit to India has been overshadowed by [[Citizenship Amendment Act protests|anti-CAA]] [[North East Delhi riots]].<ref>{{cite news | |first=Priyanka |last=Bansal |title=Trump's India trip ignored the New Delhi riots. But his silence isn't the most damning |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/think/opinion/trump-s-india-trip-ignored-new-delhi-riots-his-silence-ncna1144986 |work=NBC News |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> which left more than 40 dead and hundreds injured.<ref>{{cite news |title=As India Counts Dead, Brutality of Hindu-Muslim Riot Emerges |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2020-02-29/as-india-counts-dead-brutality-of-hindu-muslim-riot-emerges |work=U.S. News |date=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Military relations ==\n{{multiple image\n| perrow = 2/1/2/1\n| total_width = 300\n| align = \n| direction = \n| width = \n| caption_align = center\n| image1 = Yudh Abhyas 2015 National flags.jpg\n| caption1 = U.S. and Indian Army soldiers during the opening ceremony of Yudh Abhyas 2015.\n| image2 = Malabar 2012 INS Satpura (F-48) sailing alongside.jpg\n| caption2 = Sailors assigned to the guided-missile destroyer USS Halsey (DDG 97) stand in ranks as the Indian navy frigate INS Satpura (F-48) pulls alongside during a Malabar 2012 exercise.\n| image3 = Yudh Abhyas 2015 Soldiers familiarize with INSAS 1B1.jpg\n| caption3 = U.S. Soldiers with the 3rd Brigade, 2nd Infantry Division and Indian Army soldiers with the 6th Battalion of the Kumaon Regiment, fire each other's weapons during Yudh Abhyas 2015 at Joint Base Lewis-McChord.\n| image4 = A Pair of Su-30K, Mirage 2000 and USAF F-15s during Cope India 2004.JPG\n| caption4 = USAF [[F-15C]] Eagles (middle of V formation) from [[Elmendorf AFB]], Alaska, fly with IAF [[SU-30MKI]] Flankers (rear) and [[Mirage 2000]] aircraft over the Indian landscape during Cope India 04, the first bilateral fighter exercise between the two air forces in more than 40 years.\n| image5 = Sgt. Balkrishna Dave explains weapons-range safety procedures to Indian Army soldiers with the 99th Mountain Brigade before they fire American machine guns.jpg\n| caption5 = Sgt. Balkrishna Dave, an India-born U.S. Army paratrooper explains weapons range safety procedures to Indian Army soldiers before they fire American machine guns. Yudh Abhyas.\n| image6 = Indian Army Maj. Prashant Mishra is welcomed to a weapons range by Capt. Cullen Lind (cropped).jpg\n| caption6 = An [[Indian Army]] officer is greeted by a [[U.S. Army]] officer at [[Fort Bragg]], U.S., 2013.\n}}\nThe U.S. has four \"foundational\" agreements that it signs with its defence partners. The Pentagon describes the agreements as \"routine instruments that the U.S. uses to promote military cooperation with partner-nations\". American officials have stated that the agreements are not prerequisites for bilateral defence co-operation, but would make it simpler and more cost-effective to carry out activities such as refueling aircraft or ships in each other's countries and providing disaster relief.<ref>{{cite news|title=Foundational agreements won't compromise India's security: U.S.|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/foundational-agreements-wont-compromise-indias-security-us/article7213305.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=24 July 2017|language=en|date=May 16, 2015|last1=Lakshman|first1=Narayan}}</ref> The first of the four agreements, the General Security Of Military Information Agreement (GSOMIA), was signed by India and the U.S. in 2002. The agreement enables the sharing of military intelligence between the two countries and requires each country to protect the others' classified information. The second agreement, the Logistics Exchange Memorandum of Agreement (LEMOA), was signed by the two countries on 29 August 2016. The LEMOA permits the military of either country to use the others' bases for re-supplying or carrying out repairs. The agreement does not make the provision of logistical support binding on either country, and requires individual clearance for each request.<ref>{{cite news|title=India, US sign military logistics pact|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/India-US-sign-military-logistics-pact/article14598282.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=24 July 2017|language=en|date=August 30, 2016|last1=George|first1=Varghese K.}}</ref> The third agreement, Communications Compatibility and Security Agreement (COMCASA) was signed during the inaugural 2+2 dialogue in September 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pubby |first1=Manu |title=India, US ink Comcasa deal at 2+2 dialogue |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/comcasa-india-to-get-access-to-real-time-encrypted-information-from-us/articleshow/65710975.cms |work=The Economic Times |date=7 September 2018}}</ref> It is an India-specific variant of Communications and Information Security Memorandum of Agreement (CISMOA) that enables the two countries to share secure communication and exchange information on approved equipment during bilateral and multinational training exercises and operations. The fourth agreement,  Basic Exchange and Cooperation Agreement (BECA) has not yet been signed. It permits the exchange of unclassified and controlled unclassified geospatial products, topographical, nautical, and aeronautical data, products and services between India and the US [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]] (NGA). Defence Minister Manohar Parikkar stated at the signing of the LEMOA that India would eventually sign the remaining agreements.<ref>{{cite web|title=India will eventually ink other agreements pushed by US: Manohar Parrikar|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/india-will-eventually-ink-other-agreements-pushed-by-us-manohar-parrikar-3003315/|website=The Indian Express|accessdate=24 July 2017|date=30 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nHarsh V. Pant, professor of International relations at King's College London, highlighted the importance of India to US strategic planning by saying: \"India is key to the US' ability to create a stable [[balance of power (international relations)|balance of power]] in the larger Indo-Pacific and at a time of resource constraints, it needs partners like India to shore up its sagging credibility in the region in face of Chinese onslaught.\" Robert Boggs, professor of South Asia Studies at the Near East South Asia Center for Strategic Studies, opines that the US \"overestimates both India's desire to improve the relationship and the benefits doing so would bring\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Friends Without Benefits|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/united-states/friends-without-benefits|issue=January/February 2015|work=Foreign Affairs}}</ref> Neelam Deo, director of foreign policy think tank Gateway House, underscored the importance that India attaches safeguarding its national interests by saying: \"India is a big country, with its own strategic objectives and imperatives and it will act on opportunities where interests converge, as it has done in the past.\"<ref name=\"rt.com\" />\n\nRecognising India as a key to its strategic interests, the United States has sought to strengthen its relationship with India. The two countries are the world's largest democracies, and both are committed to political freedom protected by representative government. The US and India have a common interest in the free flow of commerce and resources, including through the vital sea lanes of the Indian Ocean. In recent years, India has conducted large joint military exercises with the US in the Indian Ocean.<ref>[[Exercise Malabar]]</ref>\n\nUSA as part of its foreign policy to counter China <ref>http://www.atimes.com/article/us-woos-india-100-year-alliance-china/</ref> which is now aggressively growing to the top position now held by USA, wants to make India as one of the major defence partners for which it is in talks with Indian representatives to sell highly technologically advanced predator drones.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/newsindia/trump-administration-agrees-to-supply-predator-drones-to-india/ar-AAwzvn4?ocid=spartanntp |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501161256/https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/newsindia/trump-administration-agrees-to-supply-predator-drones-to-india/ar-AAwzvn4?ocid=spartanntp |archive-date=May 1, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nIndia has floated a tender to buy 100 multi role fighter aircraft [[Indian MRCA competition]] (also called Mother of all defence deals) of around US$15 billion  under [[Narendra Modi]]'s [[Make in India]] initiative. Although the deal is yet to be finalised in 2018, Present USA Trump's administration is now pushing for sales of advanced [[F-16 jet fighter]]s,<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/business/2018/apr/07/us-defence-major-lockheed-martin-welcomes-indias-mega-procurement-initiative-for-over-100-fighter-j-1798300.html | title=US defence major Lockheed Martin welcomes India's mega procurement initiative for over 100 fighter jets}}</ref> and [[F/A-18 Super Hornet]] <ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/we-will-offer-the-latest-fa-18-boeing-india-chief/article23505309.ece | title=We will offer the latest F/A-18: Boeing India chief}}</ref>\n\nThere have been some differences, however, including US concerns over the nuclear weapons programmes and the pace of economic reforms in India. In the past, these concerns may have dominated US thinking, but today the US views India as a growing [[world power]] with which it shares common strategic interests.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} A strong partnership between the two countries will continue to address differences and shape a dynamic and collaborative future.{{who said|reason=WP:OR|date=February 2016}}\n\nIn a meeting between President [[George W. Bush]] and Prime Minister [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]] in November 2001, the two leaders expressed a strong interest in transforming the US-India bilateral relationship. High-level meetings and concrete cooperation between the two countries increased during 2002 and 2003. In January 2004, the US and India launched the \"Next Steps in Strategic Partnership\" (NSSP), which was both a milestone in the transformation of the bilateral relationship and a blueprint for its further progress.\n\nIn July 2005, Bush hosted Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] The two leaders announced the successful completion of the NSSP, as well as other agreements which further enhanced cooperation in the areas of civil nuclear, civil space, and high-technology commerce. Other initiatives announced included a US-India economic dialogue, the fight Against HIV/AIDS, disaster relief, technology cooperation, an agriculture knowledge initiative, a trade policy forum, energy dialogue, CEO Forum, and an initiative to assist each other in furthering democracy and freedom.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2005/07/20050718-6.html |title=Joint Statement Between President George W. Bush and Prime Minister Manmohan Singh |publisher=Georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov |date=18 July 2005 |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref> President Bush made a reciprocal visit to India in March 2006, during which the progress of these initiatives were reviewed, and new initiatives were launched.\n\n{{Commons category|Military relations of India and the United States}}\n\nIn June 2015, US defence secretary [[Ashton Carter]] visited India and became the first American defence secretary to visit an Indian military command. In December of the same year, [[Manohar Parrikar]] became the first Indian defence minister to visit the [[US Pacific Command]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/india-us-barack-obama-richard-verma/ |title=India, US and a year of togetherness |publisher=The Indian Express |date=2015-12-26 |accessdate=2015-12-30}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, India has rejected a proposal by the US to join naval patrols in the [[South China Sea]] alongside Japan and Australia. Defense Minister [[Manohar Parrikar]] said: \"India has never taken part in any joint patrol; we only do joint exercises. The question of joint patrol does not arise.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=India Rejects Joint Naval Patrols with US in South China Sea|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/india-rejects-joint-naval-patrols-with-us-in-south-china-sea/3231567.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311165044/http://www.voanews.com/content/india-rejects-joint-naval-patrols-with-us-in-south-china-sea/3231567.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 March 2016|publisher=Voice of America|date=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Peter Lavoy, Senior Director for South Asian Affairs at the [[United States National Security Council|U.S. National Security Council]], declared that the partnership between India and the United States under Barack Obama's administration had been \"incredibly successful\". Lavoy stated, \"I can tell you quite definitively that due to our partnerships, several terrorism plots were foiled. Indian lives and American lives were saved because of this partnership.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Many a terror plot foiled due to India-U.S. cooperation: White House|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/Many-a-terror-plot-foiled-due-to-India-U.S.-cooperation-White-House/article17008284.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=12 January 2017|date=January 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=India-US Together 'Foiled Several Terror Plots', Says Top US Official|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/india-us-cooperation-incredibly-successful-helped-foil-several-terror-plots-us-official-1646401|website=NDTV.com|accessdate=12 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Nuclear cooperation ===\nIn late September 2001, President Bush lifted sanctions imposed under the terms of the 1994 Nuclear Proliferation Prevention Act following India's nuclear tests in May 1998. A succession of non-proliferation dialogues bridged many of the gaps in understanding between the countries.\n\nIn December 2006, the US Congress passed the historic India\u2013United States Civilian Nuclear Agreement|Henry J. Hyde US\u2013India Peaceful Atomic Cooperation Act, which allows direct civilian nuclear commerce with India for the first time in 30 years. US policy had been opposed to nuclear cooperation with India in prior years because India had developed nuclear weapons against international conventions, and had never signed the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NNPT). The legislation clears the way for India to buy US nuclear reactors and fuel for civilian use.\n\nThe [[India\u2013United States Civil Nuclear Agreement]] also referred to as the \"123 Agreement\", signed on 10 October 2008 is a bilateral agreement for peaceful nuclear cooperation which governs civil nuclear trade between American and Indian firms to participate in each other's civil nuclear energy sector.<ref>[http://www.dpcc.co.in/pdf/nuclearenergyprogramme.pdf] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504112517/http://www.dpcc.co.in/pdf/nuclearenergyprogramme.pdf |date=May 4, 2012 }}</ref><ref>Schaffer, ''India and the United States'' (2010) pp 89-117</ref> For the agreement to be operational, nuclear vendors and operators must comply with India's 2010 [[Nuclear Liability Act]] which stipulates that nuclear suppliers, contractors and operators must bear financial responsibility in case of an accident.\n\nProminent industrial accidents ([[Bhopal disaster|1984 Bhopal chemical-gas disaster]] and the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|2011 Fukushima nuclear disaster]]) has led to greater scrutiny by civil society into corporate responsibility and financial liability obligations of vendors and operators of critical infrastructure. In 2010, the Indian Parliament voted the [[Nuclear Liability Act|Civil Liability for Nuclear Damage Act]] to address concerns and provide civil liability for nuclear damage and prompt compensation to the victims of a nuclear incident.\n\nOn 27 March 2019, India and the US signed an agreement to \"strengthen bilateral security and civil nuclear cooperation\" including the construction of six American nuclear reactors in India.<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. and India commit to building six nuclear power plants |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-india-nuclearnuclearpower/u-s-and-india-commit-to-building-six-nuclear-power-plants-idUSKCN1QU2UJ |website=Reuters |accessdate=28 March 2019 |language=en |date=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Economic relations ==\nThe United States is one of India's largest direct investors. From 1991 to 2004, the stock of FDI inflow has increased from US$11 million to $344.4 million, and totaling $4.13 billion. This is a compound rate increase of 57.5 percent annually. Indian direct investments abroad began in 1992, and Indian corporations and registered partnership firms are now allowed to invest in businesses up to 100 percent of their net worth. India's largest outgoing investments are in the manufacturing sector, which accounts for 54.8 percent of the country's foreign investments. The second largest are in non-financial services (software development), accounting for 35.4 percent of investments.\n\nOn 3 August 2018, India became the third Asian nation to be granted Strategic Trade Authorization-1 (STA-1) status by the United States. STA-1 enables the export of high-technology products in civil space and defence from the US to India.<ref>{{cite web |last1=PTI |first1=Lalit K. Jha |title=India third Asian nation to get STA-1 status from US |url=https://www.livemint.com/Politics/GvUiFqQuVzLnBYuM5mwFuK/India-third-Asian-nation-to-get-STA1-status-from-US.htm |website=Livemint |accessdate=5 December 2018 |language=en |date=4 August 2018 }}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=US: India fulfils all conditions, but out of Nuclear Suppliers Group due to China's veto - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/us-india-meets-all-qualifications-to-be-member-of-nsg/articleshow/65792316.cms |website=The Times of India |accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Trade relations ===\n[[File:Bush Manmohan Singh CEO Meeting.jpg|thumb|U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] and Indian Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]] during a meeting with Indian and American business leaders in [[New Delhi]].]]\n\nThe US is India's [[List of the largest trading partners of India|second largest trading partner]], and India is its [[List of the largest trading partners of the United States|9th largest trading partner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsrichestcountries.com/top_indian_importers_trade_partners.html |title=Top India Import Partners |publisher=Worldsrichestcountries.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-30}}</ref> In 2017, the US exported $25.7 billion worth of goods to India, and imported $48.6 billion worth of Indian goods.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.census.gov/foreign-trade/statistics/highlights/top/top1712yr.html |title = Foreign Trade: Data}}</ref> Major items imported from India include [[information technology]] services, [[textiles]], [[machinery]], [[Gemstone|gems]] and [[diamonds]], [[chemicals]], [[iron]] and [[steel]] products, [[coffee]], [[tea]], and other edible food products. Major American items imported by India include [[aircraft]], [[fertilisers]], [[computer hardware]], [[scrap metal]], and medical equipment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indianembassy.org/indusrel/trade.htm |title=India \u2013 U.S. Trade and Economic Relations<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=May 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512152307/http://www.indianembassy.org/indusrel/trade.htm |archive-date=May 12, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/bgn/3454.htm |title=India |publisher=U.S. Department of State |accessdate=2 April 2016 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe United States is also India's largest investment partner, with a direct investment of $10 billion (accounting for 9 percent of total foreign investment). Americans have made notable foreign investments in the Asian country's power generation, telecommunications, ports, roads, petroleum exploration and processing, and mining industries.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nAmerican imports from India amounted to $46.6 billion or 2% of its overall imports, and 15.3% of India's overall exports in 2015. The 10 major commodities exported from India to the US were:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsrichestcountries.com/top-india-exports.html |title=Top India Exports |publisher=Worldsrichestcountries.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsrichestcountries.com/top_us_imports.html |title=Top US Imports |publisher=Worldsrichestcountries.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-07}}</ref>\n\n# [[Gemstone|Gems]], [[precious metals]] and coins ($9.5 billion)\n# [[Pharmaceuticals]] ($6.1 billion)\n# [[Oil]] ($2.8 billion)\n# [[Machinery]]: $2.5 billion\n# Other textiles, worn clothing: $2.5 billion\n# Clothing (not knit or crochet): $2.2 billion\n# [[Organic chemicals]]: $2.1 billion\n# Knit or crochet clothing: $1.7 billion\n# [[Vehicles]]: $1.4 billion\n# [[Iron]] or [[steel]] products: $1.3 billion\n\n[[File:India March 2015 - 35A9754 (16295964164).jpg|thumb|US [[Food and Drug Administration]] and Indian [[List of Union Government agencies of India#Statutory Bodies|Export Inspection Council]] officials review [[memorandum of understanding]] on food safety in 2015]]\nAmerican exports to India amounted to $20.5 billion or 5.2% of India's overall imports in 2015. The 10 major commodities exported from the US to India were:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsrichestcountries.com/top_us_exports.html |title=Top US Exports |publisher=Worldsrichestcountries.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsrichestcountries.com/top-india-imports.html |title=Top India Imports |publisher=Worldsrichestcountries.com |date= |accessdate=2016-04-07}}</ref>\n\n# [[Gemstone|Gems]], [[precious metals]] and coins ($3.4 billion)\n# [[Machinery]]: $3 billion\n# [[Electronic equipment]]: $1.6 billion\n# Medical, technical equipment: $1.4 billion\n# [[Oil]]: $1.3 billion\n# Aircraft, spacecraft: $1.1 billion\n# [[Plastics]]: $815.9 million\n# [[Organic chemicals]]: $799.4 million\n# Other chemical goods: $769.1 million\n# [[Fruits]], [[nut (fruit)|nuts]]: $684.7 million\n\nIn July 2005, President Bush and Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]] created a new programme called the [[Trade Policy Forum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://2001-2009.state.gov/p/us/rm/2005/52753.htm|title=The U.S. and India: An Emerging Entente?|website=2001-2009.state.gov|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref> It is run by a representative from each nation. The United States Trade Representative was [[Rob Portman]], and the Indian Commerce Secretary then-[[Ministry of Commerce and Industry (India)|Minister of Commerce]] [[Kamal Nath]]. The goal of the programme is to increase bilateral trade and investment flow. There are five main sub-divisions of the Trade Policy Forum, including:\n\n*The [[Agricultural Trade]] group has three main objectives: agreeing on terms that will allow India to export mangoes to the United States, permitting India's [[Agricultural and Process Food Products Export Development Authority]] (APEDA) to certify Indian products to the standards of the [[U.S. Department of Agriculture]], and executing regulation procedures for approving [[edible wax]] on fruit.\n*The goals of the [[Tariff]] and Non-Tariff Barriers group include agreeing that insecticides manufactured by US companies can be sold throughout India. India had also agreed to cut special regulations on trading [[carbonated drinks]], many [[Pharmaceutical drug|medicinal drugs]], and lowering regulations on many imports that are not of an [[agricultural nature]]. Both nations have agreed to discuss improved facets of Indian regulation in the trade of [[jewellery]], [[computer parts]], [[motorcycles]], [[fertiliser]], and those tariffs that affect American exporting of [[boric acid]]. The group has also discussed matters such as those wishing to break into the accounting market, [[Indian companies]] gaining licenses for the [[telecommunications]] industry, and setting policies regarding [[Indian media]] and [[broadcasting]] markets. Other foci include the exchange of valuable information on recognizing different professional services, discussing the movement and positioning of people in developing industries, continuation of talks on financial services markets, limitation of equities, insurance, retail, joint investment in agricultural processing and transportation industries, and small business initiatives.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Relations of India and the United States}}\n{{Portal|India|United States|Politics}}\n* [[Indian Americans]]\n* [[Americans in India]]\n* [[Quadrilateral Security Dialogue]]\n* [[Foreign relations of the United States]]\n* [[